http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-3&fd=R&url=http://www.turkishdailynews.com.tr/article.php%3Fenewsid%3D74615&cid=1116589853&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ On entering northern Iraq - Turkish Daily News May 31, 2007 Thursday, May 31 2007 7:13 pm GMT+2 On entering northern Iraq Thursday, May 31, 2007 mail to a friend On entering northern Iraq As Turkey gets stressed out by terror, “Army to Iraq” discourse finds ground&#8230; Let's recall quickly: Chief of General Staff Gen. Yaþar Büyükanýt said a military operation in northern Iraq is necessary and they wait for a relevant decision to be made by political mechanism. While the heaviest military build-up of recent years goes on in the Iraq border in eastern Turkey, preparations for a possible operation were launched. The retired general at a key post to provide cooperation and communication between Turkey and the U.S. regarding the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party's (PKK) terror, removed from office by the government. Last week's suicide bombing in Ankara and confessions of terrorists caught in numerous cities in this process strengthened the conviction that the PKK targets big cities. The violation of Turkish airspace last week by two U.S. F 16s created the impression that the government and armed forces are at odds. And finally, Kurdish administrators in northern Iraq made statements in the meaning “Turkish tanks cannot find way to these lands.” Operation by press releases?: Undoubtedly the key issue needs to be clarified here is the situation that produces reservations about politics-military relations and confuses the minds. By all means, neither from the military nor the politics perspective sharing thoughts about an imaginary military operation through press releases is normal. It is even needless to say that this is against the traditions of Turkish Army and the general principles of military professional. And only to know this requires a deduction that something is odd, there is something unusual. If you ask, what is “unusual”, my answer would be: The U.S. factor&#8230; Let me elaborate this a bit more: In the good old days, “Army to Iraq” meant a “hot pursue” or a “cross border operation”. And in legal perspective, all military operations before the U.S. invasion in Iraq were held by the approval of Baghdad and in the frame of mutual agreement with the neighboring country. But now, the situation has changed. Neither the approval of Baghdad nor of Washington is the point at issue. To the opposite, statements made by both capitals give the impression of an objection and even an implicit/explicit threat against Turkey. Therefore regardless of the decision by political body in Ankara depends on the ground of “terror” it will blatantly have the characteristic of a “declaration of war”. Intervention at all odds?: Let me get to the point. I am of the opinion that the public impression of a communication break down between the military and the politics stems from that the Turkish army will be facing the U.S. forces in northern Iraq. Because the presence of Kurdish peshmerga in northern Iraq does not justify who the dominant power is in the region. Therefore it is reasonable to explain the limped communication between the Turkish Armed Forces and the government by the desire to reach a prompt conclusion in the diplomatic initiatives with Washington. Observation of escalating desire “intervention at all odds” in the Turkish army might strengthen the hands of foreign affairs having hard time to express itself in Washington. But if you ask the question whether the army will enter Iraq, the answer of course will be it is possible if suicide bombings similar to the one in Ankara continue. Apparently as long as the investigation about the suicide attack of Anafartalar Avenue in Ankara is in progress, opportunities will rise to make some new assessments beyond clarifying the incident as an attack by the PKK. I previously mentioned that there are some groups in Washington making calculations to provoke Turkish military and dragging it into the quagmire in Iraq. And the military will be worn out in a “nightmare period”, civilian decision making mechanism will be strengthened etc&#8230; I hope we will not end up loses because of the incertitude originates from election and politics discussions. The realm of the state cannot afford the games of “pretends”&#8230; &copy; 2005 Dogan Daily News Inc. About Turkish Daily News Add TDN headlines to your site Add a link to TDN from your site Created in 0.64512586593628 seconds.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/10-5&fd=R&url=http://english.people.com.cn/200705/31/eng20070531_379768.html&cid=1116589853&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ People's Daily Online -- Turkish military chief criticizes countries for supporting PKK China at a glance China in brief 2004 CPC & state organs Selected Works of Deng Xiaoping UPDATED: 20:32, May 31, 2007 Turkish military chief criticizes countries for supporting PKK Turkish Chief of General Staff Gen. Yasar Buyukanit Thursday criticized some countries for supporting the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), the semi-official Anatolia news agency reported. "There are countries supporting directly or indirectly PKK terrorism, among our allies," affirmed Buyukanit at an international symposium on "New Dimensions of Security and International Organizations," without specifying the countries. "Land mines used in and explosives such as C4, A3, A4 which are used in every murder in Turkey are not bought from supermarkets," Buyukanit said. "Countries (backing terrorism for political purposes) use double standard in combatting terrorism, and turn a blind eye to activities of persons or organizations that do not stage terrorist attacks on their own territories," Buyukanit stated. Buyukanit added that those who extend financial, logistical and propagandist support to terrorists should be deemed as terrorist. Buyukanit said there is a need for global cooperation against terrorism, reiterating that Turkish Armed Forces (TSK) are ready for international cooperation and solidarity, and sharing information and intelligence regarding security issues. An efficient international cooperation in fight against terrorism is only possible under the banner of the UN, Buyukanit said. In a bid to get rid of the threats of PKK, Turkey has recently warned that Turkish troops would launch a cross-border operation into northern in fighting against the outlawed Kurdish group. "We have earlier stated that there was a need for a cross- border operation into northern Iraq," said Buyukanit, adding " necessary planning can be made after political targets are determined." On May 22, a suicide bomb blast ripped through a crowded shopping center in the Ulus district of Turkish capital Ankara, killing seven, including the bomber, and injuring some 100 others. Officials believed the PKK was behind the attack. PKK, listed as a terrorist organization by the and the European Union, launched an armed campaign for an ethnic homeland in the mainly Kurdish southeastern Turkey in 1984, sparking decades of strife that has claimed more than 30,000 lives. The intensity of the fighting eased after PKK leader Abdullah Ocalan was captured and imprisoned in 1999, but flared up again in recent years. Comment on the story Copyright by People's Daily Online, all rights reserved
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-6&fd=R&url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/article.asp%3Fedition_id%3D1%26categ_id%3D2%26article_id%3D82643&cid=1116516999&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ The Daily Star - Politics - Nahr al-Bared refugees balk at UN proposal for temporary shelters Send to a friend Save to My Web Nahr al-Bared refugees balk at UN proposal for temporary shelters 'They won't let us go back because they want to destroy it' Thursday, May 31, 2007 BEIRUT: The UN agency responsible for Palestinian refugees is considering housing thousands of displaced Nahr al-Bared residents in temporary facilities on the outskirts of the Beddawi refugee camp. Many refugees, however, oppose the plan because of fears that it might allow the full-scale destruction of Nahr al-Bared and prevent them from returning to their homes. Finding alternative shelter for the estimated 15,000 displaced Palestinians in Beddawi is critical, because the camp has seen its population double in the past week, said UN Relief and Works Agency (UNRWA) spokeswoman Hoda Samra. "It's critical for us at this stage to look into an alternative shelter to relieve some of the congestion in the camp, because we are talking about thousands of people now," she said on Wednesday. "It's just too overcrowded. "There is huge pressure on the water and electricity networks, and they can't sustain this amount of people." Although the details have yet to be worked out, UNRWA will most likely put up prefabricated accommodations on the edge of Beddawi and install mobile generators, portable showers, toilets and water tanks, Samra added. UNRWA has not yet estimated the number of families to be housed there. Nahr al-Bared refugees demonstrated in Beddawi on Tuesday for the right to return to their homes. "When we left the camp, we decided to stay one or two days and then return to Nahr al-Bared, but they don't want us to go back because they want to destroy it," Ashraf abu-Khourz said on the phone from Beddawi. "The situation [in Nahr al-Bared] was bad when we left, and now it has become worse. People don't want to stay here. More than 20,000 people came here and Beddawi is small - there are no places to sleep or bathe. We are Muslims, and there are eight families in one classroom. Men are sleeping in the streets because they won't sleep in schools with women." The rising number of checkpoints is preventing many Palestinian students from North Lebanon from traveling to university for final exams, because residents of Beddawi and Nahr al-Bared have been detained by security forces and sometimes arrested for suspected ties to Fatah al-Islam militants, said Khourz. Huda al-Turk, another UNRWA spokeswoman working in Beddawi, said moving the displaced to temporary housing units on the outskirts of the camp is one of many solutions being debated. "So far we are still looking into other alternatives," Turk said in a phone interview from Beddawi, but she declined to give details. Beddawi, however, will not be able to sustain the current arrangement for much longer. "There is not enough space in the schools, and it is increasing the economic burden of hosting families," Turk said. "We are OK for food supplies now - even host families are receiving assistance. The critical issue is clothing now, because everyone left with nothing." The fighting has also entirely paralyzed the education systems of both camps. Finding alternative shelter for the displaced currently living in UNRWA schools in Beddawi would allow children to finish classes for the year, said Yasser Daoud, a former Nahr al-Bared resident and field worker for the NGO Nebaah in Tyre. "[The plan] is good, because the children from Nahr al-Bared and Beddawi will be able to go to school again, but people are afraid that if this type of camp is established, it will become permanent," said Daoud. Daoud has heard from other humanitarian agencies that 2,000 residences in Nahr al-Bared have already been demolished, though no formal assessment has been made because access to the camp is still restricted. "My mother, sister, and brother are still in Nahr al-Bared because they don't want to repeat what happened to them in 1948," Daoud said. "I'm worried that something will happen to them if they stay, but they feel comforted that they are at least at home." Though Nahr al-Bared residents - both those in Beddawi and those who remain in the camp - are increasingly vulnerable, with memories of the razing of the Tal al-Zaatar still fresh in their minds, another Nakba - as the catastrophe of 1948 is called - is a fate far worse than violence or living in a temporary shelter, said the head of Hamas for North Lebanon, Abu Rabih al-Chehabi. "After the Nakba of 1948, many Palestinians decided never to leave their homes again out of fear they might not return," he said. "The 20,000 people who stayed in Nahr al-Bared remember what happened then." Tags: Children, Oman, Palestinian Send to a friend Save to My Web Your feedback is important to us! We invite all our readers to share with us their views and comments about this article. Click here NOW to Comment on this Article lull in fighting allows aid into Nahr al-Bared UN approves Hariri court ISF beefs up patrols across country, especially Beirut Politicians voice mixed reactions to Lahoud's 'salvation' initiative Committee 'improving' Palestinians' lives Fadlallah accuses US of 'spoiling' internal accord Beirut? Beyrouth? Conference tackles transliteration Qatar voices reservations on Hariri tribunal Lahoud calls for 6-member 'salvation cabinet' during rare visit to Bkirki Fighting escalates between Lebanese Army, militants Visiting lawmaker: US 'strongly' backs Hariri court Rival MPs trade blame over clashes in North More Books about Lebanon War , The Daily Star. All rights reserved. to contact our syndication department for permission to republish or make other authorized use of this material. Contact the to report any problems with the site or to send you