http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-3&fd=R&url=http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/9C4F062D-71C6-4873-BA32-F65EA3588A7F.htm&cid=1116767788&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ Al Jazeera English - News - Hariri: No Ordinary Murder THURSDAY, MAY 31, 2007 6:14 MECCA TIME, 3:14 GMT There are no main images. Hariri: No ordinary murder Mark Seddon at the UN in New York Hariri supporters in Lebanon are hopeful, but the issue has exposed deep divisions [AFP] On face value, no politician or diplomat would be against prosecuting a serious crime, or bringing its perpetrators to justice. No politician or diplomat would ever say that it is acceptable to assassinate political opponents and then proceed to assassinate other key figures close to them. And yet, with a multitude of different agendas and principles whirling around, there are politicians and diplomats who are opposed to the setting-up of a UN International Tribunal to investigate the 2005 murder of Rafiq Hariri, the former Lebanese prime minister, in a massive car bomb. But this was no ordinary murder, nor is this any ordinary tribunal. who abstained on Wednesday's resolution in the UN Security Council argued that they had good reason to do so. The resolution, supported by 10 countries, including the creates a precedent &#8211; although the UN might argue that it does not. It is a Chapter Seven resolution, which is invoked in cases of threats to international peace and security. It is binding, mandatory and can be backed by force if necessary. It gives the divided Lebanese parliament until June 10 to agree to the establishment of a tribunal. The massive car bomb attack in 2005 killed nine people, including Hariri [EPA] For the first time perhaps, an individual government, in this case the Lebanese government, will be forced to co-operate with a UN-backed court. Opinion is divided in too. The country&#8217;s president is against. The country&#8217;s prime minister is for. The opposition, official and unofficial is against. And yet the demonstrations marking Hariri&#8217;s murder two years ago were so massive, that the Syrian army, seen by some as occupiers, others as protectors, withdrew from much of the country. Throughout the long process of the Hariri Inquiry, presided over by a UN-backed team, countries and people not connected to the investigation have been pointing towards Syrian complicity in the attack on Hariri's motorcade, although this remains unproved. But for those who do believe that there was Syrian involvement, an international tribunal is seen as a device that may help make their cause. However, it remains the case that the forensic investigation of the murder site, where the massive car bomb exploded, have not yet led to any suspects being named. The Lebanese parliament now has a deadline. Yet already some are asking what the UN could do enforce its decision if the parliament fails to meet it, or for some reason does not agree. Others claim that this decision by the UN Security Council will lead to yet further violence and bloodshed. Many Lebanese people ask why their own country is not going to be allowed to run its own tribunal. Questions over Syria's involvement have yet to be answered [Reuters] Although others argue that given the great divides in Lebanese society, it is quite impossible to imagine their country hosting an investigation and criminal court case of such political magnitude. The United Nations, for its part, argues that there is no precedent; that there have been international tribunals in the former , investigating war crimes and in Once again critics say that had more or less ceased to exist as a state and wasn&#8217;t functioning as a state. Lebanon, on the other hand, despite its divisions and despite the terrible damage wrought by last year&#8217;s invasion by Israel, is a functioning state, and a state that cannot agree as to whether the tribunal is a good thing or not. The many supporters of Hariri are jubilant now that they believe that justice may actually be done. They believe that a line may at last be drawn under political assassinations if the perpetrators are brought to justice. But for others in , all of this reeks of outside interference. Others still believe that far from putting a cap on the violence, the creation of an international tribunal may just fuel it. Who is right and who is wrong, we shall see in the coming weeks and months. UN votes to set up Hariri tribunal Lebanon calls for al-Hariri trial Lebanese told to agree on tribunal Extension for Hariri murder inquiry Suicide bomber hits Falluja Hariri court 'ignores constitution' On the frontline in Sri Lanka Yemen army attack claims lives Thaksin 'accepts Thai politics ban' Hariri court 'ignores constitution' Suicide bomber hits Falluja Yemen army attack claims lives Eight killed in Lebanon camp clash Cairo slum residents stage protest Hariri court 'ignores constitution' Suicide bomber hits Falluja Yemen army attack claims lives Eight killed in Lebanon camp clash Cairo slum residents stage protest
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-5&fd=R&url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2007-05-31-lugovoi-claim_N.htm&cid=1116515252&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ Spy killing suspect: Britain involved in plot - USATODAY.com How do I find it? Sign up to receive our free Daily Briefing e-newsletter and get the top news of the day in your inbox. Breaking news E-mail alerts Get breaking news in your inbox as it happens Spy killing suspect: Britain involved in plot By Jeffrey Stinson, USA TODAY LONDON &#151; The Russian businessman accused of killing former KGB agent Alexander Litvinenko here last year denied any involvement on Thursday and said that British intelligence was likely to blame for the murder, perhaps because Litvineko was working with British agents and talking too much to others about it. Andrei Lugovoi, who was accused earlier this month of the murder by British prosecutors, made his sensational claim in a televised Moscow news conference that was broadcast live here. "Even if (British special services) hadn't done it itself, it was done under its control or connivance," Lugovoi said. He said he had evidence to substantiate his claim but didn't offer it. Lugovoi, a former Russian KGB agent too, also said: &#8226; British intelligence had sought to recruit him to provide "compromising information" on Russian President Vladimir Putin. &#8226; Litvinenko worked for British intelligence and may have done something to anger the service. &#8226; If British intelligence was not to blame for Litvinenko's death, then perhaps the Russian mafia or exiled Russian oligarch Boris Berezovsky was. Berezovsky, who lives in London, was a friend and benefactor to Litvinenko. Berezovsky said that Lugovoi's press conference was proof that the Kremlin was behind the murder. "Everything about Mr. Lugovoi's words and presentation made it obvious that he is acting on Kremlin instruction," Berezovsky said in a statement. "If Mr. Lugovoi would like to prove his innocence, I suggest again that he travel to London and face trial in the (British) courts." But, Lugovoi insisted, he wasn't guilty of murdering Litvinenko, who died of poisoning from a rare radioactive isotope. "Britain is making me a scapegoat," he said. Britain's Secret Intelligence Service, MI6, has a policy of not responding to questions or commenting publicly. However, the Foreign Office brushed aside Lugovoi's allegations of British intelligence involvement. "This is a criminal matter and is not an issue of intelligence," the Foreign Office said in a statement from its press office. "A British citizen was killed in London, and (British) citizens and visitors were put at risk." Lugovoi said British agents were upset because Litvinenko bragged about his contacts with them. "In conversations with me, Litvinenko often &#8230; told me many things he shouldn't have said," Lugovoi said. "I got an impression that he was really getting out of British secret services' control. He believed that the British undervalued him and paid him too little for his service." Konstantin Kosachev, the Kremlin-connected head of the foreign affairs committee in the lower house of the Russian parliament, urged British authorities to help investigate "very serious accusations against British secret services." "I do believe they will take these new versions as seriously as it should be," Kosachev said on Lugovoi's accusations provide the latest twist in an intriguing murder case that has echoes of Cold War espionage and revenge, and which has reached the highest level of the Kremlin. It also has strained Anglo-Russian relations. And at one point, Litvinenko's radioactive poisoning prompted a widespread health alert in London and resulted in the grounding of three passenger jets. Litvinenko, 43, died from polonium-210 poisoning on Nov. 23 in a London hospital. He fell ill Nov. 1 after meeting with Lugovoi earlier in the day at London's Millennium Hotel near the U.S. Embassy. Lugovoi, now a Moscow businessman, said the meeting was about business that Litvinenko was helping him with. On his deathbed, Litvinenko accused Putin of being behind his death. Litvinenko had been a harsh Putin critic and a critic of Russia's involvement in Chechnya. He sought asylum in Britain in 2000 and later became a British citizen. Putin, also a former KGB agent, has dismissed Litvinenko's deathbed accusation, and the Kremlin has called it nonsense. Britain's director of public prosecutions, Ken Macdonald, announced on May 22 that there was sufficient evidence to charge Lugovoi with Litvinenko's murder "by deliberate poisoning" Macdonald's accusation came after Scotland Yard detectives followed a trail of radioactive material across London, to Germany and to Russia. The radioactivity prompted the British Health Protection Agency to issue a public health alert in London after traces were found at a dozen sites across the city, including three hotels and a soccer stadium. It also prompted British Airways to alert thousands of passengers who might have been exposed to low levels of radioactivity aboard three jets. In Britain, 700 people were tested for polonium contamination, and 670 were tested abroad. All were eventually released. Britain has sought to extradite Lugovoi to Britain to be charged and tried for what Macdonald called "this extraordinarily grave crime." On Thursday, the Foreign Office said it still was awaiting Russia's response to the extradition request. "Our position is clear," the Foreign Office said in the statement. "A request for the extradition of Mr. Lugovoi to face trial in a (British) court has been handed over. We await the formal Russian response." It is unlikely that Lugovoi will be handed over. The Russian constitution prevents the extradition of a Russian citizen to a foreign country to face charges. Britain has not given any indication what the motive was behind Litvinenko's murder. Nor have prosecutors provided any details of how the poison was administered. The case has worsened Russia's relations with Britain and shined an unwelcome light on Putin, who has said he will step down as president next year. To report corrections and clarifications, contact Reader Editor USA TODAY welcomes your thoughts, stories and information related to this article. Please stay on topic and be respectful of others. Keep the conversation appropriate for interested readers across the map. Newspaper Home Delivery - Subscribe Today Privacy Policy/Your California Privacy Right Add USATODAY.com RSS feeds
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.ktvu.com/news/13417265/detail.html&cid=1116515252&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ Suspect Blames British For Spy's Death - News Story - KTVU San Francisco Make KTVU.com Your Homepage Sign up for E-News Andrei Lugovoi (left) and another Russian had met in London with Alexander Litvinenko on Nov. 1, the day Litvinenko said he became ill. Suspect Blames British For Spy's Death Litvinenko Died Of Poisoning By Rare Radioactive Isotope POSTED: 2:49 am PDT May 31, 2007 The Russian businessman whom Britain has named as a suspect in the killing of ex-KGB agent Alexander Litvinenko said Thursday that he has evidence of British special services' involvement in the poisoning death. "Even if (British special services) hadn't done it itself, it was done under its control or connivance," Andrei Lugovoi told a news conference. Asked if he had evidence for the allegation, he said "I have evidence" but did not elaborate. A British government security official, who demanded anonymity in exchange for discussing Lugovoi's claims because of the sensitivity of the case, said suggestions British intelligence had involvement in Litvinenko's death were spurious. Britain last week said it had enough evidence to charge Lugovoi, who also worked for the KGB and its main successor agency the FSB, in the November killing of Litvinenko. Litvinenko, who died of poisoning by the rare radioactive isotope polonium-210, had fled to Britain several years earlier after becoming a strong critic of the Kremlin and received British citizenship. Lugovoi and another Russian had met in London with Litvinenko on Nov. 1, the day Litvinenko said he became ill. Britain has requested Lugovoi's extradition, but Russia has refused, saying the constitution does not permit such extraditions. Lugovoi has repeatedly asserted he is not guilty in the matter. On Thursday, Lugovoi also claimed that Britain had tried to recruit him to provide intelligence. British special services "asked me to collect compromising information on President (Vladimir) Putin," Lugovoi said. Lugovoi said the attempted recruitment occurred during business trips to Britain in previous years. He did not give a precise date, but indicated the alleged approach occurred in late 2005 or early 2006. London's Foreign Office, responsible for the country's overseas secret intelligence service MI6, declined to comment on Lugovoi's claim. But another government official with knowledge of Lugovoi, who also demanded anonymity because of the sensitivity of the case, said the allegations were untrue. . All rights reserved. This material may not be published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed. Military Spouses Become Scam Targets The American Red Cross said a new identity-theft scam targets family members of deployed troops. SLIDESHOW: Cathedral Near Lake Merritt Taking Shape SLIDESHOW: Coit Tower's Hidden Wonders Father Says Lohan Hooked On Alcohol And OxyContin Paula Abdul Found Her Purpose on 'Idol' Mother Pleads No Content To Richmond Baby Abandonment Officials Plan Documentary On Bay Bridge Construction 'Guru Of Ganja' Convicted Of Marijuana Charges Again Resisting Arrest Charges Dropped Against Redwood City Bodybuilder Petaluma Dog Owner Arrested After Child Attacked Porter Raiders Jersey Number Change Too Expensive Giuliani Says California Not Just A Political ATM Georgia Traveler Causes Global TB Scare Man Sentenced To 40-To-Life For SF Slaying Obama: Tax Wealthy To Pay For Health Care Clinton Picks Up LA Mayor's Endorsement Romney Pledges Salary To Charity If Elected McCain Urges Approval Of Immigration Overhaul "Law And Order" Star Set To Shake Up Republican Race Four Defendants Convicted Of Murdering 17-Year-Old In 2003 Suspect Arrested In Oakland Police Officer Shooting Menlo Park Police Warn Of Suspected Prowling Predators Coroner Says Actress' Death Was A Homicide US Supreme Court Rejects 'Night Stalker' Appeal 70-Year-Old Injured In San Francisco