http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/0-4&fd=R&url=http://www.metimes.com/storyview.php%3FStoryID%3D20070531-062650-2519r&cid=1116821733&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ 'Enemy fire' may have brought down NATO helicopter - Region - Middle East Times Thursday, May 31 2007 'Enemy fire' may have brought down NATO helicopter A NATO helicopter that came down in southern Afghanistan, killing all seven foreign soldiers on board, may have been brought down by enemy fire, the alliance's military force said Thursday. The insurgent Taliban movement said that its men shot down the Chinook in the southern province of Helmand late Wednesday. "We are able to say now that there may have been enemy fire in bringing down the helicopter," the Kabul media office for NATO's International Security Assistance Force (ISAF) said. "It could be anything from small arms fire upwards." ISAF, which includes soldiers from 37 countries, will not release the nationalities of the dead soldiers, leaving this up to their home nations. The icasualties.org Web site, which charts casualties in the operations in Afghanistan and Iraq, said that five of the dead were US nationals, but this was not confirmed by the US military here. Taliban spokesman Yousuf Ahmadi said late Wednesday that "our brothers in Helmand" had brought down the heavy transport helicopter. "The helicopter burst into flames in the sky and then crashed," he said, citing the local rebel cell that claimed to have to carried out the attack. The insurgents have made similar claims in the past but are only confirmed to have brought down one military aircraft in Afghanistan - in June 2005 when a rocket-propelled grenade (RPG) shot down a Chinook in Kunar province. All 16 soldiers on board, eight of them US Navy SEALs, were killed. On Thursday Ahmadi said that he was still not clear how the helicopter was brought down. He also claimed that 35 foreign soldiers were killed, but the rebels usually inflate their tolls and their information is often unreliable. "The helicopter might have been shot down by RPG, other ordinary weapons, or by the new anti-aircraft weapons we have got now," Ahmadi said. "The group of 30 to 35 mujahideen [holy fighters] who carried out the attack have managed to leave the area sound and safe following the clash after the crash." ISAF said Wednesday that a unit that responded to the scene of the crash was ambushed. "Under continued fire, the responding patrol called for an airstrike to eliminate the enemy threat," it said. There have been suspicions that the militants, who are allied with Al Qaeda, are trying to acquire shoulder-fired anti-aircraft weapons for their fight against the NATO force and the separate US-led coalition. In March this year, the coalition said that it carried out precision airstrikes on Taliban militants who had been helping to move anti-aircraft weapons in Helmand, killing some of them. Helmand has seen a surge in military and Taliban activity. Hardcore Taliban are said to be allied with drugs barons and foreign fighters in the province, the country's top opium producer. The province is where the Afghan and foreign military forces said that they killed the Taliban's top military commander, Mullah Dadullah, this month in the military's biggest success against the movement. The rebels have vowed to avenge the commander's death. Explosion rocks Yemeni capital Iran sets parliament vote for March 2008 'Enemy fire' may have brought down NATO helicopter Iran, EU talks seek way out of nuclear impasse 50 Baghdad gas stations to be 24-hour Was Iraq invaded to boost oil prices? Value of Exxon reserves rose by $666bn Qatar orders 80 Airbus A350s worth $16bn Malaysian woman criticizes court in religious row Israel prevents Muslim burials in Jerusalem cemetery 1967 war - One page in Egypt's history, literally British lecturers vote to back Israel boycott Jordan names first woman to head court Mideast women defy regional divides to promote peace Senegal, Gambia villages give