http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-1&fd=R&url=http://news.independent.co.uk/europe/article2600253.ece&cid=1116016460&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ A Papal blessing in a saga of love and faith - Independent Online Edition > Europe Business Analysis & Features A-Z Unis & Colleges from The Independent & The Independent on Sunday A Papal blessing in a saga of love and faith By Peter Popham in Rome Published: 31 May 2007 Kate and Gerry McCann met the Pope at his weekly general audience in St Peter's yesterday. They took away five rosaries he had blessed, including one for Madeleine, and perhaps the most intense emotions they have experienced since the horror of learning, nearly a month ago, that their four-year-old had vanished. "This is something we will cherish for the rest of our lives," Mr McCann told one of the people escorting them away from the event. "It was more personal, more pastoral, than we could ever have thought." Mrs McCann had intended to give the pontiff a copy of the now famous photograph of her daughter. But the gift came back to her, spiritually charged. Benedict took it from her hands and rested his own hand on the girl's image for several moments in silence, then with his thumb made the sign of the cross on her face and handed the photograph back. "It was a very emotional but also a very positive experience really," she said a few minutes later, at a press conference. "It's very important for us. That photograph will stay with me now." "There was recognition immediately," her husband added. "And looking at Madeleine's photograph, his touch and his thought and his words were more tender than we could ever have hoped. That will help sustain us in this most difficult time." The dignified pursuit by the McCanns of their lost child has acquired an extraordinary momentum. It has become far more than the story of one little girl and two distraught parents. It has become an emblematic saga of love and faith tested in the fire of terrible misfortune and emerging stronger; it has become a sort of contemporary parable of the power of belief. The ease with which the encounter with the Pope was arranged is part of the developing fable. Kate McCann is a devout Catholic, and yesterday, her husband said that the huge response to their tragedy "has restored my faith - my Catholic faith but also my faith in humanity." But according to gossip in Rome yesterday, the idea of a Rome pilgrimage originated not with the McCanns but with the News of the World. The British paper phoned its Rome stringer, Nick Pisa, to ask if he thought a meeting between the couple and the Pope could be set up. Pisa made inquiries and the response from the Vatican was encouraging - by which time the newspaper had lost interest. But Pisa pursued it, with the help of the British embassy, and lo and behold, it came to pass. And although the couple's campaign has turned into a huge media event, their own simplicity and sincerity shine through untarnished. The McCanns have generated a sort of charisma around themselves and their determination. If faith and resolve have the sort of potency to which the couple bear witness, Madeleine will soon be found, safe and well. "There could be a breakthrough at any minute," Mr McCann told a room full of journalists in Rome. "There could be a call to say that Madeleine has been found. We have to continue believing. "Many, many thousands and tens of thousands of people are doing small things that may make a difference, and we take strength from that. Even the smallest things by the greatest number of people that will achieve the maximum in terms of publicity around Madeleine's disappearance." Last night they were back in the Algarve, but trips to Madrid, Berlin and Amsterdam - cities from which many tourists travel to the Algarve - are planned. "One of the worst feelings was helplessness," Mr McCann said. The campaign "makes us feel we are doing everything in our power". Also in this section Lugovoy 'blackmailed to murder Litvinenko' On the barricades: Trouble in a hippie paradise Elderly guardians of French choose another 'immortal' Ahern's clash with judge spells trouble for coalition Russia tests missile which 'penetrates any defence' The true cost of putting imported food on your plate My war on electrosmog Julia Stephenson sets out to clear the airwaves The actress breaking hearts in Pinter's Betrayal How to protect children from the dangers of internet Put your questions to the Lib Dem leader The 1971 Martini Girl A life in the fast lane Introducing the IoS blogs Day in a page Find articles published on: Sign up for our free daily news update Independent News & Media &copy; 2007 Independent News and Media Limited
