http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-2&fd=R&url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3406839,00.html&cid=1116847097&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ Quartet condemns Qassams - Israel News, Ynetnews UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon Middle East mediators condemn continued attacks on Israel, Hamas arms build-up in Gaza, urge Israel to show restraint in military activity, release Palestinian ministers The Quartet of Middle East mediators harshly condemned the continued Qassam attacks on Israel on Thursday, as well as the build-up of arms by and other terror groups in the Gaza Strip, a statement released by UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon said. Quartet demands new PA gov&#39;t recognize Israel / Revived Quartet of Middle East peace negotiators underscore demand that any Palestinian government must recognize Israel. Quartet statement &#39;reaffirms commitment to meet regularly&#39; on Mideast situation The panel did not demand Israel end its military activity in the Strip, but urged Israel to exercise restraint to ensure that its security operations avoid civilian casualties or damage to civilian infrastructure in the Palestinian territories. The panel, comprised of the United States, Russia, the United Nations and the European Union, also demanded the release of Hamas ministers and parliament members arrested by Israel over the past few weeks. Ban's statement came after the Quartet meeting in Berlin in which Ban himself, Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov, American Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice, the EU's Javier Solana , European Commissioner for External Relations and European Neighbourhood Policy Benita Ferrero-Waldner and German Foreign Minister Frank-Walter Steinmeier were present. The Quartet expressed its concern of the tense internal situation in Gaza and urged the Palestinians to end all violence and honor the ceasefire. The panel also called on Palestinians to cooperate with President Mahmoud Abbas, and regional leaders in order to regain law and order in the Strip, which would bring about the release of kidnapped BBC reported Alan Johnston. The immediate and unconditional release of kidnapped IDF soldier Despite the deteriorating situation in the south, the Quartet members welcome continued dialogue between Abbas and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and urged the parties "to create an environment conducive to progress on the political horizon for Palestinian statehood." "Palestinians must know that their state will be be viable, and Israelis must know that a future state of Palestine will be a source of security, not a threat," the statement added. Alongside the demand that the Palestinian government recognize Israel and honor previous agreements, the Quartet reiterated its request that remove all illegal settlements and help improve the Palestinians' situation by opening crossings and removing roadblocks. Israel was also urged to transfer the seized Palestinian tax money to a temporary international body which would ensure the money reached the right bodies. The Quartet stated that this would lead to a real improvement in the situation. The statement further said that the Quartet welcomed the Saudi peace plan, and praised the Arab League's intention to cooperate with Jerusalem. The quartet said it planned to meet the Israelis and Palestinians next month as well as the Arab League in a bid to revive peace hopes further dimmed by a new round of violence. From Gaza to rocket-battered kibbutz Lieberman: Declare Gaza hostile political entity 5 Talkbacks for this article Please wait for the talkbacks to load Copyright &copy; Yedioth Internet. All rights reserved.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-1&fd=R&url=http://www.voanews.com/english/2007-05-31-voa6.cfm&cid=1116573508&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ VOA News - Koreas Agree to Military Talks Aimed at Preventing Naval Conflict A trusted source of news and information since 1942 Koreas Agree to Military Talks Aimed at Preventing Naval Conflict North and South Korea have set a date for military talks, aimed mainly at preventing conflict along their tense maritime border. That announcement came as diplomats from the two Koreas held talks in Seoul - where South Korea told the North it will send food aid when Pyongyang lives up to its promises on nuclear weapons. VOA's Kurt Achin has more from the South Korean capital. South Korea's Defense Ministry said Thursday that military officers from North and South will meet next Friday in Panmunjom. That village is where a 1953 armistice halted fighting, but did not formally end, the Korean War. The talks are expected to focus on preventing conflicts over the sea border. North Korean naval authorities this week announced they were patrolling the waters west of the Korean peninsula "with extra vigilance" and accused the South of "reckless military provocations." North Korea does not accept the sea border established by the United Nations in 1953, and has been involved in at least two deadly skirmishes at sea with the South since 1999. N. Korea's delegation head Kwon Ho Ung, left, talks with S. Korea's Unification Minister Lee Jae-joung during their dinner in Seoul, 31 May 2007 Separately, high-level diplomats from North and South held a second day of talks Thursday at a hotel here in Seoul. South Korean Unification Ministry spokesman Koh Kyoung-bin told reporters that the North's delegates asked about a South Korean promise to ship 400,000 tons of rice to the impoverished North. Koh says South Korea's position about providing rice to the North has not changed - it is something that will be done on the basis of trust. He says North and South should work cooperatively to resolve what he calls "a difficult situation." North Korea has missed by nearly two months a deadline it agreed to earlier this year to begin dismantling its nuclear weapons programs. South Korea says the aid it promised was predicated on North Korea's implementation of that agreement, and says the shipment will be delayed until the North takes action. Pyongyang blames the delay on a banking issue involving the transfer of $25 million of its money from a bank in Macau. No international bank has been willing to handle the transfer since the U.S. Treasury Department announced the money was linked to illegal North Korean activities. North Korea says there will be no progress on the nuclear issue until the funds are returned. Senior South Korean and U.S. officials say the financial issue will be resolved soon. US, Chinese Officials Discuss Difficult North Korean Funds Issue Top US Nuclear Negotiator Urges North Korea to End Weapons Programs S. Korea Confirms North Fired Short Range Missiles Into Sea of Japan Suicide Bombing in Fallujah Kills 20 Sporadic Fighting at Lebanese Refugee Camp Continues Rice Says Iran Must Change Course on Nuclear Issue, Halt Uranium Enrichment Suspect in Litvinenko Murder Says Former Russian Intelligence Agent Worked as British Spy NATO: Helicopter Apparently Shot Down in Afghanistan, 7 Troops Killed India, Russia Struggle to Maintain Ties From Another Era US Envoy Wraps Up Meetings in China on North Korea Banking Issue Bird Flu Spreads in Vietnam as Vigilance Wanes Terms of Use & Privacy Notice Broadcasting Board of Governors
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/16-5&fd=R&url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,21828243-24218,00.html&cid=1116798912&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ Truth and consequence | Herald Sun Welcome to Herald Sun. Corporate Photo Sales, Copyright Herald Sun Cartoons & Caricatures Memorabilia & Limited Editions Back Issues & Home Delivery Herald Sun - Sell your car for FREE Place a classified newspaper ad Send a Letter to the Editor June 01, 2007 12:00am AN ISSUE that has festered for more than 30 years threatens to drive a diplomatic wedge between Australia and Indonesia. The events surrounding the murders of five Australian newsmen in East Timor in 1975 have been obscured by a shameful combination of deceit, diplomatic compromise and political expediency. But a QC assisting a New South Wales coroner has this week recommended prosecution for war crimes of two un-named former Indonesian army officers. The prospect that someone may finally be held to account for the murders will bring joy to the families of the Balibo Five. But it will also send a shiver through the corridors of Foreign Affairs in Canberra, where maintaining a good relationship with Indonesia is a constant battle. The inquest into the death of Brian Peters has already resulted in a potentially explosive diplomatic incident. Jakarta's Governor Sutiyoso stormed out of Australia after two NSW detectives entered his Sydney hotel room and attempted to serve a summons for him to appear at the coronial inquest. Governor Sutiyoso is accused of being in Balibo in 1975 as the captain of a special operations unit, a charge he has denied. Our relations with Indonesia are extremely important, particularly in the fight against regional terrorism, and deft diplomatic footwork will be required by Foreign Affairs to ensure this issue does not sour relations with Jakarta. However, that does not mean that there should be any soft-pedalling on seeking the truth of what happened to the Balibo Five and if possible pursuing those who murdered them. The long road to Canberra Flaw in the law Your call is important High price of hired help Rudd in mess on home turf Race fans know best And the big men fly ... Search for more stories on this topic on , our news archive service. Custom built PC's - Buy a Dell PC tailored to your needs and only pay for what you want 1st mth best package + install 4 NOTHING*. Love & Relationships - Find a date near you on Match.com - # 1 Online Dating site Worldwide. It won't just be another day at the office. See the full demo. Receive our News Feeds Get your Newspaper Delivered Receive our Email Newsletter Send us your news photos Send us your story tips Get your Newspaper Delivered &copy; Herald and Weekly Times. All times AEST (GMT + 10).
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-5&fd=R&url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/middle_east/article1865883.ece&cid=1116767788&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ A United Nations vote to set up a tribunal for suspects in the killing of Rafik Hariri, former Lebanese Prime Minister, has been given an uncertain welcome in Lebanon. Cheering crowds in Beirut greeted the decision by the Security Council last night with flag waving and celebratory gunfire in the streets, but some Lebanese newspapers this morning echoed Syria&rsquo;s suggestion that a tribunal may cause even greater instability in the country." /> Fear and celebration greets Hariri tribunal vote by UN-News-World-Middle East-TimesOnline Our exclusive four-step guide to giving up before the ban Navigation - link to other main sections from here The Russians are the worst tourists in the world Fear and celebration greets Hariri tribunal vote by UN to not show photographer information --> to not show image description --> to not show enlarge option --> Nico Hines and agencies A United Nations vote to set up a tribunal for suspects in the killing of Rafik Hariri, former Lebanese Prime Minister, has been given an uncertain welcome in Lebanon. Cheering crowds in Beirut greeted the decision by the Security Council last night with flag waving and celebratory gunfire in the streets, but some Lebanese newspapers this morning echoed Syria&rsquo;s suggestion that a tribunal may cause even greater instability in the country. Hariri was killed by a truck bomb in February 2005, initial UN investigations implicated Syrian authorities in his murder. The dispute over Hariri&rsquo;s death is at the centre of a deep political crisis between the Western-backed government and the Syrian-backed opposition, led by Hezbollah. There has been no official reaction from Hezbollah to the UN resolution, but the pro-opposition al-Akhbar newspaper said setting up the court without consensus &ldquo;raises serious concern for security and stability&rdquo;. Q&A: explaining the violence in Lebanon Lebanon Army battles &lsquo;al-Qaeda&rsquo; militia Beirut struggles to heal the scars of war &ldquo;The establishment of the court according to an international resolution and without the agreement of a large segment of citizens ... widens and deepens the fracture among Lebanese,&rdquo; Omar Neshabi wrote. Tensions in the divided country have become increasingly sectarian with the most intense internal fighting since the country's civil war this month. More than 50 people have been killed in fighting between the Lebanese Army and Fatah al-Islam, a heavily-armed pro-Syrian splinter group. Hariri supporters denied that the move would lead to increased violence. &ldquo;It is a historic moment an opportunity for all Lebanese to unite... the court is not about vendettas, but about justice for all,&rdquo; said Hariri&rsquo;s son Saad, leader of the parliamentary majority. "Enough divisions. .. Let's put our energies together for the sake of the nation." The UN resolution gives the Lebanese government until June 10 to settle the arrangements for a court in a neutral country. The Lebanese parliament has until now been unable to agree over the scope and remit of a tribunal to study the circumstances of the former Prime Minister&rsquo;s death. The Security Council voted yesterday by 10-0 in favour of the tribunal, but five countries abstained. Russia, China, South Africa, Indonesia and Qatar objected to using Chapter 7 of the UN Charter, which deals with threats to international peace and allows military enforcement, as a basis for the resolution. Wang Guangya, the Chinese ambassador to the UN, warned that only a tribunal supported by all Lebanese factions would be effective. The council's move "will give rise to a series of political and legal problems, likely to add to the uncertainties embedded in the already turbulent political and security and situation in Lebanon," he said. The vote had been requested by Fouad Siniora, Lebanese Prime Minister, who claimed the trial would allow for &ldquo;the truth, the whole truth and nothing but the truth&rdquo; to be revealed. The UK and the United States were among the six sponsors of the resolution. Margaret Beckett, the Foreign Secretary, said: &ldquo;The Security Council has demonstrated its support for the government of Lebanon and its commitment to the principle that there shall be no impunity for political assassinations, in Lebanon or elsewhere.&rdquo; Reaction to the tribunal from Syria was hostile. Tishrin, the government newspaper, said in an editorial this morning that the resolution was &ldquo;absolutely an American-Israeli one and could never be regarded as an expression of the international will&rdquo;. Bashar Assad, President of Syria, has threatened not to cooperate with the court if it infringes on Syrian national sovereignty. * Town / City Save to my times Also in Middle East Fear and celebration greets Hariri tribunal vote by UN Lecturers&rsquo; union votes to back Israel boycott Anger at campaign to woo gay couples on Holy Land holidays Hunt for Britons goes on amid Iraqi violence Jobs and Gates bury the hatchet Mandela: Blair still has lots to offer world Woman dies after electricity cut off 'More tender than we could imagine' Where a spell of fame begins with a bee The Times in the Middle East A series of articles on the Middle East to mark the debut of International Edition in the region The restored Hejaz Railway is to be rebuilt as an intercity express Gaza close to civil war as Hamas threatens suicide attacks News and views from Ned Parker and Stephen Farrell Full coverage of Iraq For breaking news stories and detailed analysis Your guide to seeing the very best of what the Middle East has to offer Weather forecasts for the Middle East region Latest developments in oil, gas and other natural resources She relied on an oxygen machine. The electricity firm cut off the power. Hours later she was dead The na