http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-4&fd=R&url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/Iraq/Story/0,,2092418,00.html&cid=1116817584&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ US forces continue search for kidnapped Britons | Iraq | Guardian Unlimited Skip to main content Comment is free blog Arts & entertainment blog Interactive guides on Iraq Israel & the Middle East Full index of our special reports Cathedral city where global security thrives on SAS link 'Outside the gate, it's the wild west. We are basically a taxi service with guns' Baghdad lockdown as troops hunt for Britons Letters: Blair's policy has wrecked Iraq - and Labour Simon Jenkins: The Iraq inferno refuses to die down A multibillion dollar industry built on the most dangerous jobs in the world Five Britons kidnapped in Baghdad ambush At first there is a glimmer of hope, then dread sets in Elaborate operation inside ministry stirs fears of new tactics Troops search Sadr City for kidnapped Britons 'Iraqi police cannot control crime' Iran and US see 'positive' steps in first formal talks since hostage crisis of 1980 Hay 2007: Suzanne Goldenberg meets Richard Perle US forces continue search for kidnapped Britons Thursday May 31, 2007 US troops were today continuing to search for five Britons kidnapped in Baghdad earlier this week as new details emerged of the mock police raid in which they were seized. Last night, US vehicles took up positions around the edge of the capital's Sadr City district. The neighbourhood is a stronghold of the Mahdi Army militia, loosely led by the radical Shia cleric Moqtada al-Sadr, which some have claimed is behind the abductions. Four British security guards, employed by GardaWorld, and their client, a financial consultant working for the US company BearingPoint, were abducted from inside the finance ministry building in Baghdad shortly before noon on Tuesday. Men wearing police uniforms drove them away in the direction of Sadr City. A local policeman said a US helicopter fired on a car and home in the area shortly before dawn, killing an elderly couple who had been sleeping on their roof because of the hot weather. The US military did not comment on the alleged attack, but said its forces had arrested two "members of the secret cell terrorist network" in Sadr City today. According to a confidential Iraqi government report into the kidnapping, parts of which were leaked to the media today, the defence and interior ministers believe the raid was the work of the Mahdi Army. The report, written by the head of the finance ministry's data processing centre, where the Britons were seized, quoted General David Petraeus, the US commander in Iraq, as saying the Mahdi Army "will be profoundly sorry" if it carried out the attack. However, others doubt the militia is to blame. Sheikh Abdel al-Sattar al-Bahadli, a leading cleric with experience in hostage negotiation, told the BBC's Arab service that the Mahdi Army was not involved and wanted to build a new Iraq peacefully. According to the report, four men in civilian clothing arrived at the ministry building around 15 minutes before the kidnapping, claiming to be from the government's anti-fraud commission and checking each room before leaving. Shortly afterwards, dozens of men in army and police uniforms burst into the building, disarmed guards and went to the room in which the five Britons were working. The men were immediately taken out and driven away in a convoy of four-wheel drive vehicles. The foreign secretary, Margaret Beckett, said British officials were doing all they could to secure the "swift and safe release" of the Britons. "This is clearly a very distressing time for all concerned," she said yesterday. "Foreign Office officials are offering help and assistance to the next of kin. We are working closely with the Iraqi authorities." Tony Blair, speaking in Sierra Leone, said: "We know the dangers and challenges there [in Iraq], but we shouldn't let those who are prepared to use kidnapping and terrorism succeed." Special report: UK politics and Iraq More click-through graphics on Iraq Full text of speeches and documents Audio reports on Iraq Send it to a friend Join our dating site today Guardian Unlimited &copy; Guardian News and Media Limited 2007
