http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-3&fd=R&url=http://news.independent.co.uk/europe/article2600249.ece&cid=1116515252&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ Lugovoy 'blackmailed to murder Litvinenko' - Independent Online Edition > Europe Business Analysis & Features A-Z Unis & Colleges from The Independent & The Independent on Sunday Lugovoy 'blackmailed to murder Litvinenko' By Anne Penketh, Diplomatic Editor Published: 31 May 2007 Boris Berezovsky has disclosed details of a dramatic telephone call following the death of Alexander Litvinenko in which the exiled tycoon pleaded with the murder suspect to flee Russia for the West. Mr Berezovsky shed light on his relationship with the former FSB agent Andrei Lugovoy just before the Russian prosecutor general's office announced that swapping the two men for trial had been ruled out. Mr Berezovsky is wanted in Russia on fraud charges while Britain wants to extradite Mr Lugovoy on suspicion of murdering Mr Litvinenko, a former Russian agent, with the radioactive polonium-210. Speaking at the Miller Academy on Tuesday night, Mr Berezovsky said that he had known Mr Lugovoy, his former bodyguard, "for a long time", and trusted him. Following Mr Litvinenko's death last November, Mr Lugovoy telephoned the billionaire. "I told him - if you are not guilty, you should come to this country - go to Heathrow and talk to Scotland Yard. There is no chance you will go to jail if you are not guilty. I told him there was a polonium trail all over Europe, including in my office, and that he had to explain it. "I got no answer" from Mr Lugovoy, said Mr Berezovsky, adding that "all the steps of Lugovoy just confirm that he is behind" the poisoning. But he said that he still felt uneasy about Mr Lugovoy's role in the killing, as the former agent had previously protected Mr Berezovsky and his family in Russia, as well as the former pro-reform prime minister Yegor Gaidar. Mr Lugovoy denies any connection to the Litvinenko murder, which followed a meeting between the two men and a third former Russian security agent, Dmitri Kovtun, at a hotel in London. "Even now I have a strange impression," said Mr Berezovsky, who did not give further details but hinted that Mr Lugovoy may have been coerced into the murder. He pointed out that the former agent had been imprisoned in 2001 after attempting to spring from jail an associate of Mr Berezovsky, the former deputy director of Aeroflot Nikolai Glushkov, who had been imprisoned for fraud. Last week Mr Berezovsky told a reporter that Mr Lugovoy's life may be in danger because he was a "witness of Putin's crime". Mr Berezovsky has frequently accused the Russian President of being behind the murder of his employee, Mr Litvinenko, who also accused Mr Putin of his murder in a deathbed statement. On Tuesday evening, he repeated the accusation but denied that he had become an embarrassing guest for Britain which granted him political asylum in 2003. In a recent interview with The Guardian, he had called for the use of force to remove President Putin from power. Mr Berezovsky argued that on the contrary, thanks to his efforts, the West was now more aware of the "real danger" posed by President Putin. "In 2001, only 10 per cent thought he was dangerous in the West. Now it is 90 per cent," Mr Berezovsky said, adding that he feared for his own safety following Mr Litvinenko's death. Asked what Britain should do if Russia continued to refuse to extradite the suspect for trial, Mr Berezovsky replied: "This is not just a problem for Britain, this is a problem for the West." He suggested that economic sanctions could be invoked. Russia points out that it is constitutionally barred from extraditing a Russian citizen for trial abroad, but has offered to put Mr Lugovoy on trial in Moscow. Britain has ruled that out. Also in this section A Papal blessing in a saga of love and faith On the barricades: Trouble in a hippie paradise Elderly guardians of French choose another 'immortal' Ahern's clash with judge spells trouble for coalition Russia tests missile which 'penetrates any defence' The true cost of putting imported food on your plate My war on electrosmog Julia Stephenson sets out to clear the airwaves The actress breaking hearts in Pinter's Betrayal How to protect children from the dangers of internet Put your questions to the Lib Dem leader The 1971 Martini Girl A life in the fast lane Introducing the IoS blogs Day in a page Find articles published on: Sign up for our free daily news update Independent News & Media &copy; 2007 Independent News and Media Limited
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.adnki.com/index_2Level_English.php%3Fcat%3DSecurity%26loid%3D8.0.416890096%26par%3D&cid=1116847097&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ U.N.: ASIA-PACIFIC REGION KEY IN FIGHT AGAINST POVERTY UN secretary general Ban Ki-moon U.N.: ASIA-PACIFIC REGION KEY IN FIGHT AGAINST POVERTY New York, 22 May (AKI) - Asia-Pacific - with most of the world's people and some of its fastest-growing economies - is crucial to meeting anti-poverty targets, Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon told regional leaders meeting in Kazakhstan. "With Asia-Pacific now home to two thirds of the world's population, the level of progress achieved in your region will be a critical factor in determining whether our global efforts to reach the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) will succeed or fail," he sai, in a message delivered by Jose Antonio Ocampo, Under-Secretary-General for Economic and Social Affairs Monday. Officials from 62 United Nations Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific (UNESCAP) member governments are in Almaty for the week-long meeting 60 years after the body, then known as the Economic Commission for Asia and the Far East, was founded in Shanghai. The MDGs, time-bound targets for slashing poverty and other ills by the year 2015, are at the top of the meeting's agenda. "I am encouraged by the fact that, in recent decades, the countries of Asia and the Pacific have seen a record number of people lifted out of poverty," Ban said. "Still, over 600 million fellow human beings who have not benefited from the region's economic gains continue to face a daily struggle to survive," he added. He urged redoubled efforts to fight extreme poverty within UNESCAP's &#8220;Green Growth,&#8221; or environmentally sustainable approach. To help the countries which are lagging behind, government ministers from across the region have expressed support for a "road map that aims to have all countries 'marginally' off-track to be back on-track towards reaching MDGs by 2009, those 'moderately' off-track to be in line by 2011, and those in the 'severely' off-track category on target by the end of 2013. At the meeting, Kim Hak-Su, Executive Secretary of UNESCAP, applauded the endorsement of the plan. "Your commitment is vital to the regional road map," he told the ministers. "2007 marks the midway point to 2015. It is important that the countries come together to ensure the targets are met," he said. The road-map is expected to be endorsed by the Commission session when it concludes on Wednesday, 23 May. LEBANON: SOLDIER KILLED BY SNIPER IN PALESTINIAN CAMP MIDDLE EAST: QUARTET APPEALS FOR RELEASE OF BBC REPORTER LEBANON: SYRIANS HELD FOR ALLEGEDLY SPYING ON SAUDI AMBASSADOR SRI LANKA: WAR BETWEEN REBEL FACTIONS LOOMS PAKISTAN: MISSING PEOPLE'S RELATIVES 'MISLED' BY INTELLIGENCE AGENCY DARFUR: HUNDREDS OF SUDANESE FLEE TO TOWN IN CENTRAL AFRICAN REPUBLIC LEBANON: INDEPENDENT U.N. TEAM TO ASSESS BORDER SECURITY INDONESIA-PAKISTAN: DEFENCE COOPERATION TO BE BOOSTED TURKEY: SIX ARRESTED OVER PLOT TO ATTACK CHRISTIAN PASTOR MIDDLE EAST: ISRAEL SHOULD LAUNCH OWN ROCKETS ON GAZA, MINISTERS SAY
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-6&fd=R&url=http://www.thesun.co.uk/article/0,,2005320001-2007250203,00.html&cid=1116016460&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ The Sun Online - Maddie: Hope for parents at Vatican Make This Your Home Page Letters - Dear Sun Top 25 viral emails Falklands 25 Years on Got A Story? 63000 News of the World Meet the maker of this giant snack Find out what the future holds Van Dam leaves after next PPV Hope for parents at Vatican Holy help ... the Pope blesses Maddie's photo as Kate and Gerry watch Pope's prayer for Maddie Cops in Maddie suspect blunder Psychic joins Maddie hunt Poignant airport clip of Maddie Haunted by tot in PJs FULL MADDIE INDEX &#155;&#155; Babe Bro! Who's your fave? Golly! Are retro dolls racist? Are you too fat for NHS ops? McClaren: Is he a 'joke'? COMMENT ON THIS STORY BRAVE Kate McCann fought tears as she told the Pope yesterday: &#147;We need to find Madeleine.&#148; The grief-stricken mother&#146;s voice was barely audible as she made her impassioned plea. Battling to stay in control, Kate stood before His Holiness Benedict XVI during the open-air audience in historic St Peter&#146;s Square. With husband Gerry by her side, she murmured: &#147;Thank you from all of us just so want need to find Madeleine.&#148; Then her voice faltered as tears began to well, while The Pontiff stretched out his hands &#151; and gently clasped hers. The Pope whispered back his reassurance. And Kate replied: &#147;I know that. Yes.&#148; He took Gerry&#146;s hand too and the distraught dad bowed to kiss the Holy Father&#146;s. Kate offered: &#147;Father. Do you, er, want to see a picture of Madeleine?&#148; As the picture of the smiling four-year-old was passed to the Pope, he recognised it as the image that has touched millions around the world. Kate said, &#147;That&#146;s her. Yes&#148;, as she pressed it into his hands. Concern ... the Holy Father listens to Kate and, right, McCanns appeal to Italian people for help Then in a final act of comfort for the devout Roman Catholic couple, The Pope blessed the picture with a sign of the cross. &#147;Thank you,&#148; Kate whispered, her voice tailing off. The GP had been clutching Maddie&#146;s favourite pink stuffed toy, Cuddle Cat, as the Pontiff offered words of comfort. And she said of the 30-second meeting: &#147;He was very kind, very sincere. He said he would pray for us and our family and continue to have faith for us for Madeleine&#146;s safe return to us. &#147;I thanked him first of all for letting us meet him for his prayers. It has been a lovely day. &#147;It was a very positive experience. I think it has only made us stronger and lifted us up more. Maddie ... missing for past 28 days &#147;There is so much good out there. It is really evident and it has really helped us.&#148; Gerry, a hospital consultant, added: &#147;It was more personal than I could ever imagine it could have been. &#147;His touch, words and thoughts were more tender than we could have thought. &#147;In other circumstances, of course, it would be the highlight for any Catholic to meet the Pope. &#147;But it is tainted with the very marked realisation that our daughter is still missing.&#148; He added: &#147;One evil act with the abduction of Madeleine seems to have generated so much good. It has restored my faith in humanity.&#148; The couple had waited for two hours at the front of 30,000 pilgrims at the general audience. They struggled to stay composed amid the pomp and pageantry. And at one point Kate buckled when an English priest read out a special papal blessing for &#147;your children and your loved ones&#148;. They arrived in Rome on a private jet from Portugal and stayed overnight in the residence of the British Ambassador to the Vatican. And they were among only around 50 pilgrims given the honour of a personal papal meeting. Yet amid the sea of smiling faces, they stood out because of their tears. Kate stayed composed by toying with a set of black rosary beads. She frequently looked down at two photos of Maddie, while Gerry slipped a comforting arm around her waist and squeezed her shoulder. At other times he held her close whenever her burden of pain appeared too great. Kate kept her head bowed at one point as little girls &#151; not much older than Maddie &#151; laughed excitedly in seats beside her as the Pope neared. A Vatican spokesman, the Reverend Ciro Benedettini, said the Pope was happy to meet the couple after a request from British Cardinal Cormac Murphy-O&#146;Connor. He said: &#147;We are talking about a family drama that has touched world public opinion. &#147;It could not but touch the Holy Father, especially since these people are Catholics. The Holy Father is considered the father of all, therefore he was personally touched as a father.&#148; Last night the couple, from Rothley, Leicestershire, jetted back to Portugal to be reunited with their two-year-old twins Amelie and Sean. Kate said: &#147;We just can&#146;t even think about going home. Our total preoccupation is finding Madeleine. &#147;At the end of the day this is for Madeleine. I don&#146;t like talking about this publicly but you have got to put your own feelings aside. &#147;You can never lose sight of what we are trying to do &#151; find Madeleine.&#148; Gerry added: &#147;We&#146;re still in the middle of a race and we do not know how long it is going to be. I don&#146;t know how we will have changed but we will never be the same again.&#148; Email to a friend FULL MADDIE INDEX &#155;&#155; Send your messages of support. ADD YOUR VIEWS HERE Share your views with others, in real time, on our discussion boards. DISCUSS WITH OTHER SUN READERS&#160; What's In MY Sun? MY Sun provides Your Stories, gives you the chance to discuss and comment on the stories. Install The Sun toolbar &#187; &#169; 2006 News Group Newspapers Ltd . "The Sun", "Sun", "Sun Online" are registered trademarks or trade names of News Group Newspapers Limited. This 