http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-3&fd=R&url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/iraq/article1865754.ece&cid=1116817584&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ American soldiers pressed on with the search for five kidnapped Britons in Baghdad today on a day of heavy violence in Iraq, in which at least 25 people were killed in a suicide bombing. Residents of Sadr City, the northern suburb that is a stronghold of the al-Mahdi Army, the Shia militia suspected of carrying out the abductions, said that an early morning helicopter strike had killed two people while US commanders said two suspected terrorists had been detained." /> Hunt for Britons goes on amid Iraqi violence-News-World-Iraq-TimesOnline Our exclusive four-step guide to giving up before the ban Navigation - link to other main sections from here The size of England&rsquo;s defeat was more than a minor dent Hunt for Britons goes on amid Iraqi violence Sam Knight and agencies American soldiers pressed on with the search for five kidnapped Britons in Baghdad today on a day of heavy violence in Iraq, in which at least 25 people were killed in a suicide bombing. Residents of Sadr City, the northern suburb that is a stronghold of the al-Mahdi Army, the Shia militia suspected of carrying out the abductions, said that an early morning helicopter strike had killed two people while US commanders said two suspected terrorists had been detained. Dozens of Bradley fighting vehicles and Humvees carried US troops into the Shia district last night where they continued their so-far fruitless house-to-house searches. A cleric who runs the Sadr City political office of Hojatoleslam Moqtada al-Sadr, the spiritual head of the al-Mahdi Army, said his building was stormed at 3am. Witnesses said the two people who died were an elderly couple sleeping on their roof to avoid the heat. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office said there had been no major overnight developments in the search for the four British security guards and IT consultant who were taken hostage in carefully planned raid on the Iraqi Finance Ministry on Tuesday. Fears are growing for abducted Britons SAS team is diverted to join hunt Iraq holds breath before vital summer A spokeswoman said that Kim Howells, the Foreign Office Minister, was in Basra yesterday and discussed the operation to secure their release with the Iraqi Foreign Minister, Hoshiyar Zebari. Meanwhile the Iraqi Government released a statement saying that a special military unit had been set up to help the search and that it had "undertaken urgent measures to determine the facts and locate the kidnappers...The government condemns this crime and is doing all it can to ensure the immediate release of the kidnapped Britons". The FCO spokeswoman said that the British diplomats and military officials in charge of the operation were keeping their minds open as to which insurgent group might have been responsible for the kidnapping, despite a leaked incident report that appeared to point the finger of blame at the al-Mahdi Army, whose Basra leader was killed in a joint British and Iraqi operation last week. "There is obviously lots of speculation but we have to keep an open mind and deal in facts rather than pick one theory over another," she said. The report, obtained by the Associated Press, was reportedly written by Fatih-Allah, the director general of the Finance Ministry's data processing centre, where the Britons were seized, and quoted the top US Commander in Iraq, General David Petraeus, saying that the al-Mahdi Army &ldquo;will be profoundly sorry" if it carried out the abductions. The account of the kidnapping said that Iraq&rsquo;s Defence and Interior ministers believed the al-Mahdi Army of being behind the raid and corroborated other witness reports, which described gunmen claiming to be from the Government's anti-corruption body taking the hostages away in a convoy of 19 four-wheel-drive vehicles. The report said that a group of four men in civilian clothes reportedly scouted the Finance Ministry building 15 minutes before the larger party arrived. The al-Mahdi Army is under close scrutiny after the reappearance in Iraq last Friday of Hojatoleslam al-Sadr, their young and charismatic leader, who has been in hiding for the last four months during the massive US-Iraqi security operation considered a last-ditch attempt to stabilise the country. The militia has been reportedly frayed by the cleric's absence, fuelling speculation that the Britons were taken by an extremist splinter group. Meanwhile other reports have claimed that the kidnapping bore the hallmark of Sunni insurgents and that the al-Mahdi Army is not involved at all. In another operation in Baghdad today, US forces, backed by helicopter gunships, fought for several hours with armed men suspected of ties to al-Qaeda. Reports said that al-Qaeda militants, who consider Baghdad&rsquo;s Amariyah neighborhood part of their so-called Islamic State of Iraq, opened fire on students about to attend their final exams. Iraqi police said that 45 men were detained and the local leader of the militants, known as Haji Hameed, was killed. There was no comment from the US military. Outside the capital, at least 25 people were killed and 50 were wounded when a suicide bomber blew up a police recruiting centre in Fallujah, in unstable Anbar province 65km (40 miles) west of Baghdad. The recruiting centre, in a primary school, had opened on Sunday. "A cleric who runs the Sadr City political office of Hojatoleslam Moqtada al-Sadr...said his building was stormed at 3am. Witnesses said the two people who died were an elderly couple sleeping on their roof to avoid the heat." If you cannot find the abductees, might as well just kill some old people. That will show them. * Town / City Save to my times Hunt for Britons goes on amid Iraqi violence Who let the kidnappers in, and who let them out? US troops search Baghdad houses as fears grow for abducted Britons Jobs and Gates bury 