http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-6&fd=R&url=http://www.charlotte.com/409/story/141937.html&cid=1116847097&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ Charlotte Observer | 05/31/2007 | Splintering creates chaos in Middle East Sign in to your Classified Account Sign in to Classifieds Posted on Thu, May. 31, 2007 Splintering creates chaos in Middle East Iraq, Gaza represent frightening trend toward disintegration I'm heading to the Middle East at a time of two sobering anniversaries that reveal much about the dangerous state of the region. May 20 was the anniversary of the formation of Iraq's first fully elected and constitutional government, led by Nouri al-Maliki. Today, the Maliki government is virtually nonexistent, and Iraq is in chaos. June 5-6 will be the 40th anniversary of the outbreak of the 1967 Six-Day War. That was a conflict precipitated by Egypt in which a victorious Israel occupied the West Bank and Gaza. After decades of inconclusive peace talks, Israel still effectively controls these territories. An elected Palestinian Authority is on the verge of collapse, and near anarchy reigns in Gaza. Iraq and Gaza represent a frightening trend toward disintegration in the region, especially in places where elections have replaced Arab autocrats. On my trip to Israel, Jordan, Iraq and Syria, I plan to examine whether there's any way to enhance stability in the Middle East. I'm not very optimistic. In the wake of the Iraq war and the breakdown of any Israeli-Palestinian peace process, my Mideast contacts say the regional chaos will only get worse.I was in Baghdad last year when the Maliki government took office. It was clear that this was a government in name only. The constitutional system the U.S. helped set up creates a weak prime minister with little power. Congress and the White House can demand benchmarks, but Maliki can't deliver. Iraq shows the fallacy of White House dreams of social engineering. Many of the Middle East's authoritarian regimes -- like Egypt and Syria -- are fragile and dependent on the military and secret police to keep power. But knocking off a dictator, in states where no civic institutions have been allowed to grow, won't create a democratic nirvana -- especially when religious political parties are the strongest political forces, and best positioned to win the vote. I'm returning to Baghdad to see if there is the slightest chance Iraq's political leaders can come together to stop the sectarian killing. Are two states still possible? The tragic situation on the West Bank and in Gaza also reflects misunderstanding of the region. The death of Palestinian President Yasser Arafat offered the White House the last best chance to encourage a two-state solution. It passed up the chance. Arafat's successor, Mahmoud Abbas, and his Palestinian Authority were weak, but Abbas was committed to two states, side by side. Had Gaza been returned to him via peace talks, his Fatah party would have been strengthened -- and Hamas undermined. Instead, the U.S. backed Prime Minister Ariel Sharon's plan to withdraw unilaterally from Gaza. This bolstered Hamas' argument that their violent tactics drove out the Israelis. The undercutting of Abbas led to the predictable disintegration of the Palestinian Authority. Even as President Bush was telling Americans that Gaza would morph into a model democracy, its impoverished society was collapsing. Its people, desperate for services, voted for Hamas. A trip to Israel on the 40th anniversary of the Six-Day War must focus on the future of the West Bank and Gaza. I want to hear whether Israelis and Palestinian have any new ideas about how to create two states -- or whether this concept is no longer valid. The answer is crucial for the entire Middle East and for U.S. interests in the region. If the two-state solution is dead, Palestinian society will fragment further under Israeli control. That, in turn, would inspire Palestinian Islamists to strike out with greater ferocity at Israel and beyond. It is this fragmentation that creates breeding grounds for small and violent Islamist groups -- the most frightening trend in the region. Such groups are far more difficult to deal with than rulers of states. When Israel fought the Six-Day War, it fought regimes with recognized leaders with whom it could negotiate a truce or a peace. I am heading for a region where splinter groups -- in Iraq, in Lebanon, in Gaza -- can hold off armies and have no desire to negotiate. The most urgent question in today's Middle East is how to counter that trend -- and whether diplomacy can succeed where military might cannot. Trudy Rubin is a columnist for The Philadelphia Inquirer, P.O. Box 8263, Philadelphia, PA 19101. E-mail: &#150; All United States &#150; &#150; All Job Categories &#150; QA - Quality Control Restaurant - Food Service Skilled Labor - Trades About the Real Cities Network About the McClatchy Company
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-1&fd=R&url=http://www.theage.com.au/news/in-depth/northern-exposure/2007/05/31/1180205421656.html&cid=1116354652&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ Northern exposure - In Depth - theage.com.au Welcome to The Age. From left, Skye Bortoli and Ayesha Future are in Anchorage campaigning to save whales. IN THE winter of 2004, a humpback whale slid below the swell at Byron Bay in northern New South Wales, just as a camera shutter clicked. Humpback tails are as individual as faces or fingerprints, and this tail was particularly elegant. Wide, symmetrical and creamy white, it was unmarked by the frequent scars of battle and survival. A thin, dark line traced the tail's trailing edge, which swept out to finely balanced fluke tips. At a notch midway between the tips were two small dots - flaws in the perfection. Photo identification is a widely used tool to discover more about the lives of humpbacks, and the Australian researchers kept this picture in a catalogue. Recently it was matched with two other images: one at Hervey Bay in Queensland 14 months later and another shot by a New Zealander at the Balleny Islands, in Antarctica, in February last year. The same whale is unmistakable in each image, even to a layman. The subtle confirmation is those two dots. The images of this whale were recorded in a scientific paper and put before the International Whaling Commission. They confirm a legend, tell of the real link Australians are building with these animals, and point to conflict ahead. The legend was that the Ballenys forsaken, isolated rock outcrops on the edge of the Ross Sea were a reliable waypoint for humpbacks on the annual migration to and from Antarctica. Here was solid evidence. The link came through years of collecting tail fluke ID photographs, and months of skilled analysis to match the images - sifting needles from the pictorial haystack. In those collections, two other tails were found at the Ballenys, about 5000 kilometres from their Australian haunts. This is a reminder that among an estimated 7000 east Australian humpbacks and perhaps 14,000 that call the west coast home, as many as one in five has been photographed, and so is a known individual. And that points to the conflict. This week at the IWC gathering in Anchorage, Alaska, Australia and other anti-whaling nations are trying to persuade Japan not to harpoon these humpbacks next summer. If they fail, the odds are that in places where the whalers normally hunt - such as the Ballenys - about 10 of the Japanese haul of 50 will be these known individuals. Aside from their deaths by harpoon, they will be points of scientific light extinguished, no longer illuminating the little that is known about their travels. And by some Australians they will also be mourned. A 14-year-old Aboriginal girl from Port Stephens, NSW, carried wisdom far beyond her years to the IWC meeting this week. She was there to plead, with her friends, for the humpbacks. "These are our humpbacks," said Skye Bortoli. "The first thing they see when they come from their mother's womb is the Australian coastline. So if anyone should determine what happens to them, it's us." But the fate of these humpback whales depends on international manoeuvrings, public policy and direct intervention. At the IWC, there is Japan's drive to resume commercial whaling, and the future of the organisation itself. An electoral contest is also developing between Labor and the Coalition over whaling that may spur greater action. And if all of these developments fail to halt the harpoons, there are the protest ships. Sea Shepherd found and attacked the Japanese fleet last summer - at the Ballenys. Humpbacks first appeared on the Japanese list when it unveiled an increased "research" plan in 2005. It trialled the plan over the next two years with fin whales, partly to determine whether it could handle whales larger than minkes on the factory ship Nisshin Maru. From next summer it would mean killing up to 935 minkes, 50 fin whales, which are second only to the blue in size, and 50 humpbacks. Japan maintains that it is trying to determine whether there has been a shift in the population balance. It claims the fully protected humpbacks, and also fin whales, are now out-competing minkes. Despite the apparent conflict with this theory, it also doubled its minke kill. This week - even though it lost weeks of "research" to a fatal ship fire, and only took three of 10 planned fins (the largest was a pregnant female weighing a hefty 65 tonnes) - Japanese officials formally concluded that the feasibility study worked. The Nisshin Maru has been repaired and will go ahead with the full program, whaling across a vast stretch of ocean far south of Australia. It has been a growing and multi-pronged campaign on the part of Japan. In "diplomatic" terms, it reached its zenith at the 2006 IWC meeting. The pro-whaling side won a non-binding vote that declared the moratorium on commercial whaling was no longer necessary. Anti-whaling nations, however, responded to the shock outcome by recruiting their own new members this year, welcoming aboard Greece, Slovenia, Ecuador, Cyprus and Croatia. This week more than 70 nations came to the meeting in Anchorage. Even before the delegates arrived, there were signs that the IWC's strange international vote race may be ending. Each side held its own think tank earlier this year on how to reform the organisation. They independently agreed on some things, such as the need to reduce the level of insults and confrontation in its meetings. The usually strident Japanese delegation withdrew some of its normal demands and its leader, Joji Morishita, surprised reporters by declaring: "Actually, I'm not interested in the numbers game any more." The issue that had threatened to blow up for the US hosts, a quota of bowhead whales for Alaskan Eskimos, was defused with Japan before the meeting began. Instead, the two early pressure points have been the Southern Ocean humpback hunt, and a long-standing Japanese bid to gain a minke whale quota for its small, remnant coastal whaling industry. Morishita, the cool, greying face of Japanese whaling diplomacy, made it clear that this coastal minke catch was important to his whaling industry. "Japan believes the fate of this proposal will test whether the IWC can be revived as a responsible international organisation." If the addition of humpbacks to its scientific research was Japan's bargaining chip to allow the coastal catch, it failed. Anti-whaling nations said as a group that this was commercial whaling, not the indigenous subsistence hunt that it was claimed to be. And there would be no whale-trading. Patrick Ramage, from the International Fund for Animal Welfare, called Japan's proposal a bad joke. "It's the equivalent of a robber coming in to your house and saying 'you know what? I'm going to take a few less of your family heirlooms this year. Why don't you do something in return.' " Australian Environment Minister Malcolm Turnbull ruled out support of anything but the indigenous subsistence hunt. Instead, with the New Zealand Conservation Minister, Chris Carter, he turned up the heat on Japan. The two ministers asked it to call off the humpback hunt as a gesture of goodwill. Turnbull said the humpbacks should be seen as part of the life of Australia's coastal communities. "What we have been saying privately and publicly to our friends in Japan is that the inclusion of the humpbacks is a highly provocative act," he said. "It is calculated to undermine dramatically the standing, the affection, the relationship between Australia and the Japanese people." In the face of these public warnings, Morishita kept open his offer of talks on the issue, which Australia and New Zealand took up. The first round left Turnbull sounding gloomy. "No one has changed the Japanese mind here for what, 20 years? So you'd have to be quite an optimist to believe that you could change their mind in the course of 24 hours." But as the meeting rolled on, Japan softened its demand for the coastal hunt, raising hope among conservationists. "I think we may soon have a deal," Ramage said. Turnbull stayed bullish: "The Japanese are really trying to use the humpbacks as hostages. Let's be honest. In effect, we are seeing a return to the pre-IWC days of unilateral whaling." But he insisted he was also willing to talk. If the humpback hunt is not dropped by Japan, it threatens to become an obstacle for the Howard Government at the federal election. As green issues go, climate and water far outrank whaling today. But Australians still love their whales. An independent Galaxy opinion poll for the conservation group Australians for Animals recently found that only 11 per cent of Australians believed the Howard Government was doing enough to protect humpbacks, and 81 per cent wanted it to do more. The poll found that 77 per cent of Australians approved of the ALP policy to take Japan to international courts. Within a week of this finding, Labor upped the ante. Opposition Leader Kevin Rudd released a policy declaring illegal the killing of whales by Japan in waters claimed as an Australian Whale Sanctuary off the Australian Antarctic Territory. Controversially, it also said that Labor would enforce Australian law prohibiting whaling in these waters, monitor whalers operating there, and maintain the option of boarding their ships. The use of the navy was an option, and evidence gathered could be used in an international court case. Japan repeatedly refused to comment on the Labor policy, though Turnbull quickly attacked it as suggesting high-seas piracy. However the idea of putting extra heat on Japan in the Antarctic resonated in some government seats with whale-watching interests. The parliamentary secretary for industry, Bob Baldwin, said it would be a good use of taxpayers' money to give the new Antarctic air link the task of detecting whaling ships in order to name and shame them. Meanwhile, the perils of human control over humpback whales are being driven home at the IWC. The Caribbean island of St Vincent was given the right to catch up to four a year in a hotly opposed indigenous hunt. The history of this hunt is younger than the 1851 novel Moby Dick. The inadequate weapons used mean protracted deaths for the humpbacks, usually female. And the whale is consumed in a beachside barbecue, complete with plentiful liquor stalls and gawping tourists. In an effort to find some harmony in the IWC, Australia joined in approving St Vincent's new quota. The consensus was greeted with applause. The International Whaling Commission was set up in 1946 to "manage the proper conservation of whale stocks and thus make possible the orderly development of the whaling industry". It failed at the task as whale stocks were devastated in the mid-20th century, leading to the moratorium on commercial whaling that came into force in 1986. The only permitted whaling quotas are for aboriginal subsistence whaling. About 360 whales were hunted under that category in the past year. Japan, however, has used the IWC's "scientific research" loophole to license its own whaling. It kills about 1000 whales a year - mainly minkes. Controversially, this year, it has added 50 humpbacks to its list. Yesterday, the IWC passed a resolution condemning Japan's scientific slaughter of whales and calling for its end. But the only way to close the loophole is to have every nation agree to change the IWC's founding convention. There are now 77 member nations in the IWC, broadly split into pro and anti-whaling camps. A handful of countries are neutral. Australia is among the anti-whaling group. In the year since the last meeting, a total of 1616 whales were reported hunted and killed to the IWC. Andrew Darby is The Age's Hobart correspondent. His book, Harpoon - into the heart of whaling , will be published by Allen & Unwin in August. When you see news happening