http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/18-4&fd=R&url=http://www.africasia.com/services/news/newsitem.php%3Farea%3Dmideast%26item%3D070531142600.64k5owe3.php&cid=1116825594&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ enter E-mail for our Where to find us News from the Middle East WASHINGTON, May 31 (AFP) US confirms jailing of third Iranian-American by Tehran The United States confirmed on Thursday that Iranian authorities had jailed a third Iranian-American, Ali Shakeri, apparently on spying charges, and it called for the immediate release of all three. Shakeri, a California-based businessman who also works for a private conflict-resolution group called the Center for Citizen Peacebuilding, has been detained in Tehran's Evin prison, State Department deputy spokesman Tom Casey said. Iranian officials confirmed on Tuesday that two other US-Iranian scholars, Haleh Esfandiari and Kian Tajbakhsh, had been detained on spying charges and that a fourth dual national, journalist Parnaz Azima, faced similar allegations but had not been arrested. US confirms jailing of third Iranian-American by Tehran Israel prevents Muslim burials in Jerusalem cemetery Bush, Olmert to meet June 19: White House Six more US soldiers die in Iraq Turkey, Iran agree to expand energy cooperation France welcomes UN resolution on Hariri killers Another soldier, 8 militants killed in Lebanon standoff: army Suicide bomber kills Fallujah policeman Solana urges Iran to be flexible on nuclear issue Islamist sniper kills Lebanese soldier Explosion rocks Yemeni capital Turkish army says confronting Barzani forces a possibility 15 killed when army strikes Yemen petrol station Egypt court denies opposition leader's bid for freedom Israel PM to meet Bush in Washington next month Saudi prisoner dies in Guantanamo, apparent suicide: military US-Russia clashes sour G8 meeting Britain hails UN vote on Hariri court Two Palestinians killed in West Bank car blast British lecturers vote to back Israel boycott &copy; Copyright IC Pu