n northern Gaza Strip, but no injuries were reported. Following a meeting of the Israeli cabinet held on Sunday, Israeli Premier Ehud Olmert vowed to expand military actions on Gaza militants, whether militants halt or continue rockets attacks on Israel. Meanwhile, Hamas movement's armed wing spokesman vowed that attacks on Israel would continue "as long as Israel continues its aggression on our people and the men of resistance."
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-4&fd=R&url=http://www.businessday.co.za/articles/world.aspx%3FID%3DBD4A479446&cid=1116756038&ei=m-xeRsngAYf40QHv7IzQDQ Business Day - News Worth Knowing Thursday, 31 May 2007 Â - Economy & Business Â - Comment & Analysis Â - The Bottom Line Â - Technology @ Work Posted to the web on: 31 May 2007 West is close to imposing new sanctions on IranÂ  POTSDAM &#x2014; Major industrial states threatened yesterday to support &#x201C;further appropriate measures&#x201D; if Iran failed to comply with United Nations (UN) resolutions demanding that it suspend nuclear enrichment. Iran&#x2019;s chief nuclear negotiator Ali Larijani reiterated that he would not give in to demands that his country suspend uranium enrichment over fears it is developing nuclear weapons. Iran denies that it is secretly developing atom bombs. Larijani is due to hold talks today with EU foreign policy chief Javier Solana amid a long-running argument between Iran and the west over the Islamic republic&#x2019;s nuclear programme. Diplomats do not expect a breakthrough. &#x201C;If Iran continues to ignore demands of the Security Council, we will support further appropriate measures as agreed in Resolution 1747,&#x201D; the Group of Eight (G-8) foreign ministers said in a statement issued at a meeting in Potsdam, Germany. The G-8 statement expressed &#x201C;deep regret that Iran, as we saw in the latest report by the director general (of the International Atomic Energy Agency), has continued to expand its enrichment activities&#x201D;. Security Council resolution 1747 gave Tehran a 60-day deadline to freeze all enrichment work. Iran ignored the deadline, which expired last week. The term &#x201C;appropriate measures&#x201D; is widely seen as diplomatic code for sanctions. The council has already imposed two rounds of sanctions on Iran for failing to suspend uranium enrichment. Besides major western powers and Japan, the G-8 also includes Russia, which has backed previous UN resolutions while stressing Iran&#x2019;s right to a peaceful nuclear programme. Today&#x2019;s meeting between Larijani and Solana, acting on behalf of world powers, will be the first since US and Iranian officials held rare face-to-face discussions in Iraq, although atomic affairs were not on the agenda in Baghdad. The US , which accuses Iran of seeking to build an atomic bomb, has been leading efforts to isolate it over its nuclear programme and also says it is stirring up violence in Iraq. Iran denies both charges. &#x201C;Suspension is not a solution to Iran&#x2019;s nuclear issue &#x2026; Iran cannot accept suspension,&#x201D; Larijani said in Tehran before leaving for Madrid, where he will meet Solana. &#x201C;We have no conditions and we are ready for constructive talks but we will not accept any preconditions. We are ready to remove concerns over Iran&#x2019;s atomic issue.&#x201D; Previous meetings have failed to persuade Tehran to obey UN resolutions demanding it halt enrichment. &#x201C;We are ready to hold talks without preconditions, any day, any time, but they (the Europeans) should change their logic and use this opportunity which Iran has created for constructive talks. Previous methods will lead them nowhere,&#x201D; Larijani said. Also at Potsdam yesterday Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov warned other world powers not to decide the fate of Kosovo on their own, saying talks between only Belgrade and Pristina could solve a row over independence for the Serbian province. US Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice yesterday dismissed separate concerns from Russia over a proposed US missile shield in Poland and the Czech republic. BDFM Publishers (Pty) Ltd disclaims all liability for any loss, damage, injury or expense however caused, arising from the use of or reliance upon, in any manner, the information provided through this service and does not warrant the truth, accuracy or completeness of the information provided. Copyright Â© 2005 B