http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-1&fd=R&url=http://uk.equilibri.net/article/6895/Venezuela__the_RCTV_case_-_is_democracy_threatened_&cid=1116439417&ei=j_1eRtaKJ4e80QGxx5TNDQ Venezuela: the RCTV case - is democracy threatened? Venezuela: the RCTV case - is democracy threatened? ');" onmouseout="hideMenu();"> Asia - Pacific ');" onmouseout="hideMenu();"> Middle East ');" onmouseout="hideMenu();"> Asia - Pacific ');" onmouseout="hideMenu();"> Middle East Venezuela: the RCTV case - is democracy threatened? Even though it had been widely announced, first of all by the rumours of the political world and then by the Miraflores Palace itself, the closure of RCTV (Radio Caracas Television) has given rise to a further polarisation of an already divided Venezuelan population. The TV broadcaster&#039;s supporters, who had already manifested publicly, have fought with the police and 11 police officers have been injured. Some deem the decision to close the popular network as a further sign of the authoritarian aims of Hugo Chavez, while others consider it as the right sanction for a TV that had supported the 2002 coup. At 11:59:59 pm on Sunday May 27th RCTV went off air for the first time in 53 years. The channel was founded on 15th November 1953 and it is universally considered, both by its supporters and detractors, the "mother" of all the national broadcasters and a sort of historical memory of contemporary Venezuelan culture. However, in 20 minutes alone, it was replaced by the newborn public broadcaster, TVes (Venezuelan Social Television) that the government presented as the new frontier in media communication. The closing of RCTV didn&#039;t come out of the blue: months ago, while the expiry date for the Government&#039;s decisions on frequency allocations was approaching, Hugo Chavez announced that the popular channel would not continue broadcasting. During the last few months the disputes over the decision have gradually worsened and resulted in demonstrations held before and after the closure of the channel, demonstrations during which 11 police officers were injured. The dynamics are being investigated by the Judiciary which will have to identify who began the fight, the demonstrators or the Police. According to the explanations of Juan Romero, chief of the Metropolitan Police, some particularly violent indivduals charged the police cordon in an attempt to force their way through and enter the headquarters of the Conatel (National Telecommunications Council). The latter responded by firing tear gas and using water canons but without being able, at the beginning, to halt the demonstration which was brought to an end only hours later when, always according to Romero, some shots were fired at the police. The military claim such a high level of tension was created in order to have "a dead body the Government could be blamed for". Even though such an explosion of violence from the population hadn&#039;t been seen since 2002, the central issue remains the decision of the criticised President Chavez to force the oldest, most popular Venezuelan channel off the air; such a decision offers an important base on which to review the status of the freedom of expression in the Bolivarian Republic. The first voices raised in protest against the decisions of the Miraflores Palace were obviously those of RCTV. The CEO claimed that this "marks a turn towards totalitarianism" and re-confirmed the dual decisions of the management body: starting from that moment to continue broadcasting at least three newscast per day through channels offered by supportive broadcasters and through the Web and, then, taking legal action in the national court and in the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights. RCTV will present the Commission, where it is likely the Organisation of American States (OAS) will also appeal for the same reasons, the accusations according to which the closure was decided on, the channel had been opposed to the executive throughout the years; such an attitude would thus bring a sort of "censura ad libitum". As concerns the Venezuelan Court, it will have to decide whether article 210 of the 2002 Telecommunication law has been violated; according to the law the renewal of frequencies allocation should automatically be granted up to 2027 or at least up to 2022. The polls by Datanalisi confirmed that dissatisfaction cuts across the civil society too: more than 70% of the interviewees declared they are against the Government&#039;s choice while only 13% said they were favourable. Gonzalo Marroquin, president of SIP (Inter-American Press Association) refers to the Chapultepec Treaty according to which neither the media nor their frequencies shall be used to earn benefits or to punish opponents. Teodoro Petkoff, founder of MAS (Movement to Socialism) advanced the issue talking about "a further step towards a media dictatorship". The issue quickly surpassed the national borders and found a wide echo abroad: the European Union expressed its serious concern and reiterated its request that Venezuela respect the fundamental rights and the freedom of expression. The Peruvian President, Alan Garcia, and the Mexican Secretary of Foreign Affairs, Patricia Espinosa, immediately denounced the event while the ASDER (Salvadorian Broadcasters&#039; Association) suspended, as a sign of solidarity, its broadcast for 5 minutes on May 28th; the same protest took place in Costa Rica on the same day. The Colombian trade unionists also shared the view that Chavez&#039;s decision is the umpteenth symptom of its authoritarianism; the White House may follow this view since it has already accused the Head of State in Caracas of having infringed the laws concerning the freedom of thought and of expression. However not all the national and international communities are lined up against Chavez. Several manifestations supporting his decision have taken place in front of the Venezuelan embassies in Costa Rica, El Salvador and Mexico and resulted also in some fights with RCTV supporters. In Venezuela too the outcome of the debate has not been decided yet, despite the findings of the sociological survey institutes. First of all Chavez&#039;s approval rating remains high and does not fall under 65%, the figure which had assured his victory at the Presidential elections. Secondly, there are indeed two theories that endorse the decision to close the TV channel. First of all some of the Head of State&#039;s supporters quote the Constitution itself where it is clearly stated that the renewal of the allocations is never automatic and the Government has, according to the so-called Primary Law, the right/duty to deliberate on the use of the national radio and television network. Moreover, the Executive can, among its other competences, create a public television that is currently meant to be TVes. According to this point of view, Miraflores Palace did not infringe any fundamental law, let alone decrease the importance of private channels which would have simply been downsized in order to allow a more equal distribution of frequencies. In fact, according to the Media Watch Global, before RCTV was closed, 79 (97%) out of 81 TV channels were private and the situation was similar for the radios (706 private out of 709). So, if any political connotation were excluded, the issue would only consist in the implementation of the national constitutional laws. The second theory is that of "Self-Defence", whose supporters ideally line up with Modesto Emilio Guerrero. Their theory bases itself on the explanation given by Chavez himself on May 25th according to which if Globovision, RCTV, Televen and Venevision remained in the hands of the oligarchy, they would threaten the government, the revolution and democracy. By exploiting false information and funding terrorism (the way in which funds were granted has not been clearly specified), RCTV would have thus repeatedly tried, from 2002 up to today, to destabilise the State thus deliberately ignoring the social responsibility the media have. In this optic, the President&#039;s decision would be no more than an action made to protect national stability and, partially, to restore moral values. In order to justify the closure of RCTV in fact, Caracas also brought up two events that had been forgotten: during Andrea Peres&#039; mandate the TV had been involved in two scandals: tax evasion and broadcast of pornographic images. It is not rare, indeed it is common, for the government of a nation to deliberate on the assignment of frequencies needed for radio and TV broadcasting. The clamour the RCTV case rose was not related to the action itself but rather to the meaning such an action might have in the near future. It had been ascertained long ago that Chavez wished to "hush up" the inconvenient channel that, according to him, was guilty of having supported the 2002 coup. Such an accusation comes from the fact that during the fights no images of the Head of State&#039;s supporters had been shown not even when they had been charged by their opponents. No negotiations and no legal remedy convinced Chavez to give up his aim; the High Court too was not of help given its ambiguous attitude: even though it had not deliberated yet on Garnier&#039;s appeals it did not hesitate in assigning the frequencies to the new TVes, thus tacitly supporting the projects of the executive and sustaining the suspicion the Bolivarian Revolution invalidated the Judiciary&#039;s impartiality. Rumours according to which Globovision, Venevision and Televen too are being targeted by the President cast a shadow on the general situation of the press and freedom of expression under Chavez. Even though we examine the situation through the lenses of the "self-defence" supporters, the reaction appears at least too drastic. Even though media undoubtedly have an important weight in contemporary politics, it is difficult to suppose a TV channel might turn the roots of a country upside down. Without prejudice to the fact that the legitimacy of the TV closure has not been ascertained yet and even though we admitted that the Constitution might endorse this decision, the refusal to assign frequencies has a considerable importance since it seems to lay bare some of the national management&#039;s weaknesses. Either the willingness of the President, now publicly revealed, to constantly monitor information, or its excessive fear the latter might jeopardise its position. Equally, the recent events have underlined, for the first time since 2004, that the society, even its pro-Chavist part, does not accept as a dogma any order whatsoever imposed by the Head of the State even though, according to the polls, it still holds trust in its leader. The risk of the society&#039;s polarisation seems to be very likely, as is an isolation on the international scene, if we consider the aggressive affirmations Miraflores addressed to the world community as a response to the criticism received: as the official press releases state, such criticism is considered by Venezuelan Government as a violation of the international treaties and meddling in Venezuela&#039;s internal decisions. If it is not meant to be a mere act of force against the opposition, the RCTV issue should represent for the Government of Caracas an occasion to deeply reflect on its future actions in order to avoid the explosion of national and international conflicts and a likely (and probably ruinous) fall into authoritarianism. Contents produced by Equilibri cannot be reproduced in whole or in part. In the case of commercial use written permission must be issued by the copyright holder (Equilibri Srl). Published articles may not reflect the opinion of the owners of this site. Registered with the Tribunale di Firenze on the 19th January, 2004 Venezuela: the RCTV case - is democracy threatened? Venezuela &ndash; Cuba: affinities and differences between Castro&rsquo;s and Chavez&rsquo;s 