shu and Abashiri on Hokkaido, to kill minke whales. Japan already kills 220 minke from the stock in the Okhotsk Sea-East Pacific region which is adjacent to the towns it nominated. These are killed as part of the research hunts. Meat from all the whales killed by Japan is sold throughout the country and called ``research by-product.&#39;&#39; The IWC, which holds a United Nations mandate to conserve global whale stocks, voted unanimously on May 28 for the renewal of several aboriginal whaling quotas, including one for Eskimos in Alaska and Russia that allows them to hunt 280 bowhead whales during the next five years. Pro-whaling countries, including several African and Caribbean nations, support Japan&#39;s coastal whaling plan. ``Japan&#39;s proposal appears no different than Alaska&#39;s bowhead whaling,&#39;&#39; said Gregory Bowen, Grenada&#39;s IWC commissioner. ``The only difference is that one is called small- coastal hunting and other is called aboriginal whaling.&#39;&#39; Opposition to Japan&#39;s proposal stems in part from the research hunts, which it began a year after the commission banned commercial whaling in 1986. Japan says the program is necessary to prove whale stocks have recovered sufficiently to sustain a return to commercial whaling. This year it cut short its Southern hunt after the main ship caught fire. Japan has also angered anti-whaling nations with its plan to add humpbacks, an endangered species, to the minke and fin whales it kills on expeditions to the Southern Ocean Sanctuary in Antarctica. Last Updated: May 31, 2007 04:47 EDT Wages Fell for Fifth Month in April, Stifling Consumer-Spending Recovery Dollar Weakens Most Against Euro in Two Weeks on First-Quarter U.S. Growth Stocks in Tokyo Rise on Fed&#39;s U.S. Outlook, Led by Sony; Komatsu Jumps
