http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/11-2&fd=R&url=http://www.dailystar.com.lb/article.asp%3Fedition_id%3D10%26categ_id%3D2%26article_id%3D82653&cid=1116197449&ei=j_1eRtaKJ4e80QGxx5TNDQ The Daily Star - Politics - Abbas wins credit for seeking Palestinian cease-fire Send to a friend Save to My Web Abbas wins credit for seeking Palestinian cease-fire Compiled by Daily Star staff Thursday, May 31, 2007 The UN Security Council called Wednesday for an "immediate end" to the fighting between rival Palestinian factions in Gaza and welcomed efforts by Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas to arrange a cease-fire. In Berlin, the so-called Quartet of Middle East peace mediators - the United States, Russia, the European Union and the United Nations - held talks on how to overcome the new flare-up in fighting. Ban said he hoped the meeting would help "facilitate the peace process." In a non-binding statement read by US Ambassador to the UN Zalmay Khalilzad, who holds the Security Council's rotating presidency this month, members urged all Palestinian parties to join them in "supporting the call of President Abbas for an immediate end to the violence." They expressed their "grave concern" at the breakdown of the cease-fire in Gaza, welcomed Abbas' efforts for an end to the fighting and expressed appreciation for Egypt's "active support" in this regard. Palestinian UN observer Riad Mansour called the statement "a small step in the right direction" and expressed hope that "we can build on it for a larger involvement" of the council in the situation. Mansour added, however, that he would have preferred a call by the council for a Palestinian-Israeli cease-fire in Gaza and the occupied West Bank, an end to Israeli air strikes and the dispatch of UN observers to monitor the cease-fire. Echoing the UN's statement, foreign ministers for the Group of Eight major industrialized powers meeting in Germany urged the Palestinian leadership to stop fighters from firing rockets into Israel and urged the Israelis to show restraint in their response. Israel's security Cabinet decided Wednesday to continue "attacks and military pressure on terrorist groups, mainly Hamas and Islamic Jihad," Prime Minister Ehud Olmert's office said in a statement. "It was emphasized [at the meeting] that Israel is not conducting any negotiations for a cease-fire with the terrorist organizations," the statement said. On Tuesday, Abbas proposed a truce covering the Gaza Strip, and then extending the cease-fire to the occupied West Bank within a month. In an interview with Britain's Guardian newspaper, exiled Hamas political leader Khaled Meshaal defended the rocket strikes and warned the conflict might be heading for "an explosion." "The Palestinians are steadfast and there are many ways of resisting according to opportunities and conditions," he said. "Now the international community is trying to undermine Hamas. That will lead to an explosion that will be in the face of the Israeli occupation. The damage will affect the stability of the entire region." Meshaal was apparently referring to crippling Western sanctions imposed on the Palestinian Authority. In Cairo, a Hamas delegation began talks Wednesday with Egyptian intelligence officials on ways to consolidate the truce between Hamas and Abbas' Fatah, officials said. But immediately after arriving in Egypt, top Hamas official Said Siam accused Fatah of balking on a reconciliation agreement signed in Mecca earlier this year under which the two sides formed a national unity government. Siam specifically mentioned Mohammad Dahlan, a powerful Fatah leader in the Gaza strip and a top security adviser to Abbas, of orchestrating the fight against Hamas. Palestinian Prime Minister Ismail Haniyya, after talks with Abbas, said Wednesday in Gaza that he hoped the talks in Egypt would "reach real understandings and close the painful door" of Palestinian infighting, and also at the same time "open the door of real power sharing." In the occupied West Bank, Israeli forces detained the mayor of a small town near Nablus as part of a crackdown on Hamas politicians. Dozens of Hamas officials have been seized since last week. In the past week it has seized Education Minister Nassereddine al-Shaer and another minister along with more than 30 other Palestinian officials. It detained more than 30 Palestinian legislators last year, mostly from Hamas, after the Islamist group won power in January's parliamentary elections. The speaker of the European Parliament, Hans-Gert Poettering, used a speech to the Israeli Parliament on Wednesday to urge Israel to free the Palestinian legislators. "The situation seems critical in a way that it has not for a long time," he said. "The European Parliament calls on the one hand for the release of the abducted Israeli soldiers, Ehud Goldwasser, Eldad Regev [seized by Hizbullah in July 2006] and Gilad Shalit [captured near Gaza by Palestinian militants in June 2006], as well as of the British correspondent Alan Johnston [kidnapped by Palestinian militants on March 12 of this year], and on the other for the imprisoned members of Parliament and other politicians, including Education Minister Nassereddine al-Shaer, to be released," Poettering said. He also called on Israel to release some $700 million of Palestinian customs revenue it has collected but not passed on to the Palestinian government. "This is Palestinian money," he said. "This is not money which belongs to others." But Olmert rejected the call. "The prime minister emphasized that he will not transfer funds to the Palestinian Authority so long as there is concern that the funds will be used for terrorist ends," Olmert's office said in a statement after he held talks with Poettering Earlier, the Israeli Army killed two Hamas members in an air strike in the Gaza Strip. Several civilians were wounded in the attack and a house was damaged, ambulance crews said. - Send to a friend Save to My Web Your feedback is impo