http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-1&fd=R&url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/headline/world/4849308.html&cid=1116821733&ei=j_1eRtaKJ4e80QGxx5TNDQ 5 U.S. soldiers, 2 others killed in Afghan copter crash | Chron.com - Houston Chronicle " width="11" height="11" border="0"> Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Travel News & Features Legal & Public Notices May 31, 2007, 4:15AM 5 U.S. soldiers, 2 others killed in Afghan copter crash Taliban claim Chinook downed by rocket; rescuers ambushed Chopper attack: 7 military killed in Afghanistan KABUL, Afghanistan — NATO troops today secured the wreckage of a CH-47 Chinook helicopter apparently shot down by Taliban militants, an attack that killed everyone on board — five U.S. soldiers, a Canadian and a Briton, officials said. "There will be a full investigation," said Maj. John Thomas, a spokesman for NATO's International Security Assistance Force. "We will try to determine everything that happened and to fully investigate the site." A U.S. military official, who insisted on speaking anonymously because the crash was still under investigation, said initial reports suggested the helicopter was hit with a rocket-propelled grenade Wednesday evening. A purported Taliban spokesman, Qari Yousef Ahmadi, claimed in a phone call to The Associated Press that militants shot the helicopter down in southern Helmand province, the world's largest opium poppy-growing region where combat has been heavy in recent months. Ahmadi did not offer any proof for his claim, but he specified the helicopter crashed in the Kajaki district hours before NATO reported that information. Kajaki is the site of a hydroelectric dam and the scene of recent fighting. NATO said troops going to the crash site were ambushed by enemy fighters and the unit called in an airstrike "to eliminate the enemy threat." It did not say if the troops were from the U.S.-led coalition, NATO's force or the Afghan army. One civilian was injured by gunfire. The CH-47 Chinook, a heavy transport helicopter with two rotors, can carry around 40 soldiers plus a small crew. The fact it was flying at night suggested the aircraft might have been carrying troops on a nighttime air assault. Kajaki is the site of a large U.S.-funded hydroelectric dam now being repaired so it can provide electricity to the southern city of Kandahar. British troops, who make up the bulk of the forces in Helmand province, have been engaged in fierce fighting around the dam protecting it. The NATO force, which is responsible for a countrywide counterinsurgency campaign, has 37,000 soldiers, including about 14,000 Americans. There are 12,000 U.S. troops in the separate U.S.-led coalition, which trains the Afghan army and conducts Special Forces anti-terrorism operations. Helicopter crashes in Afghanistan have been relatively rare. A Chinook crashed in February in the southern province of Zabul, killing eight U.S. personnel. Officials ruled out enemy fire as the cause. In May 2006, another Chinook crashed attempting a nighttime landing on a small mountaintop in eastern Kunar province, killing 10 U.S. soldiers. In 2005, a U.S. helicopter crashed in Kunar, after apparently being hit by a rocket-propelled grenade, killing 16 Americans. Elsewhere, a senior military officer said the U.S. had "the Taliban on their heels" in Afghanistan. Brig. Gen. Perry Wiggins, deputy director of operations for the Joint Chiefs of Staff, told Pentagon reporters that "the Taliban has suffered numerous losses and has suffered losses to their senior leadership over this past month" in southern and eastern Afghanistan. As a result, the Taliban has "reverted to asymmetric-type, small-scale, high-profile attacks," he said. Mullah Dadullah, a one-legged veteran who orchestrated an intensifying campaign of suicide attacks and beheadings, was killed in an operation in southern Afghanistan this month. He had been considered the top Taliban field commander. Still, Wiggins said that as the poppy harvest ends, more insurgents might join the battle. "So the fight's not over," he said. "But we'll continue to take the offensive through several of the operations we have in Afghanistan, and hopefully ... continue to inflict casualties on the Taliban." Associated Press writers Lolita Baldor in Washington and Noor Khan in Kandahar, Afghanistan, contributed to this report. 25 dead in bombing at Fallujah police recruiting station Israel strikes northern Gaza Strip in response to rocket fire Lugovoi alleges British involvement in spy poisoning death Tropical Storm Barbara forms off coast of Mexico 5 U.S. soldiers, 2 others killed in Afghan copter crash U.S., Iraqi forces hunt for kidnapped Britons 4 American oil workers freed in Nigeria 5 Americans among 7 dead in Afghan crash 5 Americans, 2 more die in Afghan crash Taliban releases 3 Afghan aid workers Taliban free 3 Afghan aid workers, announce new offensive Taliban launches new Afghan operation NATO says copter down in Afghanistan Southern Afghan clash kills 24 militants, 7 civilians 3 Afghan aid workers released by Taliban British soldier killed in Afghanistan U.S. bombers pound Taliban positions Buy Photos & Page Prints 2005-Present Historic Page Prints 1901-2004 Copyright Notice & Privacy Policy
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-3&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601086%26sid%3DabZxsP7rSAWs%26refer%3Dlatin_america&cid=1116439417&ei=j_1eRtaKJ4e80QGxx5TNDQ , May 31 12:55 , May 31 17:55 , Jun 01 01:55 Australia & New Zealand Venezuela on Way to `Media Hegemony,&#39; Rosales Says (Update2) By Theresa Bradley and Alex Kennedy May 30 (Bloomberg) -- Venezuelan opposition leader Manuel Rosales urged citizens to flood the streets in peaceful protest against this week&#39;s closure of Radio Caracas Television, saying President Hugo Chavez is creating ``media hegemony.&#39;&#39; Rosales, who won 37 percent of the vote in the Dec. 3 presidential election, called for a referendum to decide whether RCTV, as the network is known, should be put back on the air. As he spoke, thousands of university students rallied in support of the station for a fifth day. Protests will probably continue all week, said Jeyson Gomez, a 23-year-old a medical student. ``We&#39;ll give the last breaths of our lives to be sure Venezuela doesn&#39;t lose its freedoms and democracy doesn&#39;t die,&#39;&#39; Rosales, the governor of Zulia state, told supporters at a news conference in Caracas. The government&#39;s May 27 closure of RCTV, the most-watched network and a critic of the president, has rallied the opposition and sparked international criticism that the government is seeking to control the media and drown out dissent. The five days of disorder across the country mark the longest stretch of anti-Chavez demonstrations since March 2004, when protests demanding a recall referendum left nine dead. Concern that protests will turn violent led investors to sell dollar and bolivar-denominated bonds in the local market and move money out of the country, pushing down the currency in the unregulated market, traders said. The yield on the government&#39;s 6.25 percent dollar bond due in 2017, known as TICC, rose 18 basis points, or 0.18 percentage point, to 4.94 percent, the highest since November 17, at 4 p.m. New York time, according to Banco Bilbao Vizcaya Argentaria SA. ``The country is extremely polarized, the macro-economic environment is very uncertain, and the conditions of legal stability are also very blurry,&#39;&#39; said Carlos Caicedo, head of Latin American analysis at Exclusive Analysis in London. ``The government probably didn&#39;t foresee such a strong popular support for Radio Caracas and the media in general.&#39;&#39; Chavez&#39;s government has financed scores of new community and national media friendly to its agenda, boosting its reach to include seven open television signals, two cable networks, and 28 community TV channels, along with 200 local radio signals, 110 websites, 40 regional and 4 national newspapers, Rosales said today. ``Here is proof of how this government is advancing to an informational and media hegemony in this country,&#39;&#39; said Rosales, one of the country&#39;s two governors, among a total of 23, who aren&#39;t aligned with Chavez&#39;s coalition. About 182 people have been arrested for their role in allegedly violent acts during protests across Venezuela this week, including 107 minors, Justice Minister Pedro Carreno said last night. At least 17 police officers were hurt in clashes with protesters in Caracas. Most suffered only light cuts and one fractured his shin, Metropolitan Police Chief Juan Francisco Romero Figueroa said. Neither Romero nor Carreno released figures on the number of protesters injured. U.S. House Speaker Nancy Pelosi called on Chavez to reconsider his ``ill-advised decision&#39;&#39; to shut down RCTV, noting the House of Representatives may ask the Organization of American States to ``respond appropriately&#39;&#39; to his move. ``President Chavez should know that efforts to suppress the media will not only ultimately fail, but are also a detriment to one of the pillars of democracy: freedom of expression,&#39;&#39; Pelosi said in a statement released today from Washington. Texas Democrat Sheila Jackson Lee, who visited Caracas in February, seconded that appeal, asking Chavez&#39;s government ``to abide by its commitments under the Universal Declaration of Human Rights and the Inter-American Democratic Charter and to reverse policies that limit freedom of expression.&#39;&#39; Disturbances were reported last night in Caracas&#39;s Chacao municipality, an opposition stronghold. The private news network Globovision aired a home video of clashes on one of Chacao&#39;s main thoroughfares, showing a group of armed men crowded in high-rise vestibule shooting into the street as scattered debris piles burned in the deserted roadway. A second video showed Metropolitan police shooting at a group of people who scaled a fence to take refuge in an office building&#39;s lobby. According to Metropolitan Police Chief Romero, the video is part of a ``media war&#39;&#39; intended to misrepresent events and incite more violence, state media said. ``Why don&#39;t they say they were shooting plastic bullets, permitted by international law for use in disturbances to the public order?&#39;&#39; Romero asked. ``Why don&#39;t they show the videos where police are talking to the students and trying to dissuade them in the first place?&#39;&#39; To contact the reporters on this story: Theresa Bradley in Caracas at ; Guillermo Parra-Bernal in Caracas at Last Updated: May 30, 2007 18:21 EDT Venezuela&#39;s Local Bonds Rebound as Street Protests Against Chavez Ease Colombia Peso Breaks 1,900-Per-Dollar-Barrier on Bank&#39;s Inflation Emphasis Chinese Iron-Ore Demand, Steel Output May Exceed Expectations, Vale Says
