http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-6&fd=R&url=http://news.scotsman.com/international.cfm%3Fid%3D848482007&cid=1116817584&ei=j_1eRtaKJ4e80QGxx5TNDQ Scotsman.com News - International - Warning of security lapses in Iraq as hunt for abducted Britons goes on Your browser has been unable to load the stylesheet that accompanies this page. The page is still readable. [ Register now - free! Thursday, 31st May 2007 Thu 31 May 2007 Warning of security lapses in Iraq as hunt for abducted Britons goes on SECURITY experts warned yesterday of serious lapses in intelligence in Iraq as coalition forces kept up the hunt for the four British bodyguards and one computer expert snatched from Baghdad's finance ministry. Tuesday's daylight raid was carried out by men in police uniforms, and officials said they were no closer to finding out who took them or why. Holes in intelligence gathering in Iraq are said to have opened up since policing and security matters were handed to the Baghdad government, and one source told the BBC the kidnapping would never have happened a year ago. As fears grew for the men's wellbeing, with no demand or even communication from the hostage-takers, Tony Blair, the Prime Minister, insisted the kidnapping would not deter Britain from trying to bring peace to Iraq. Speaking from Freetown, in Sierra Leone, his only remark on the crisis was: "We know the dangers and challenges there [in Iraq] but we shouldn't let those that are prepared to use kidnapping and terror succeed." His reluctance to be drawn further underscores the sensitivity of the situation. Hoshyar Zebari, Iraq's foreign minister, was more forthcoming, blaming the kidnap on the Shia militants, the Mahdi army. "We are pursuing this case very vigorously," he told BBC Radio 4's Today programme. "It has been a known fact for some time that the interior ministry police, security units and forces are corrupt, are penetrated. "This issue is a very serious, challenging fact to the government itself." Mr Zebari pointed to the dozens of people who had confidently sealed off the building, set up roadblocks and broken into the ministry as proof it had been an inside job. He said the kidnappings took place in a Shia-dominated area and could have been conducted by the Mahdi army, led by the Shiite cleric Muqtada al-Sadr. But he gave an upbeat assessment of the outcome. "Their safety is our top priority...I don't think they will finish them," he said. "They are using them for bargaining, but they have not contacted anybody yet." However, Abdul Mahdi al-Mutiri, a top official in Sadr's political movement, denied responsibility and insisted the scale and organisation of Tuesday's operation would have been beyond the Mahdi army's capabilities. Separate reports claimed the kidnap group was a Shia-backed death squad not linked to the Mahdi army. On the streets of Sadr City, Baghdad's Shia suburb, United States and Iraqi soldiers scoured homes for the five Britons. But locals raised concerns about their heavy-handed tactics, with residents reporting the demolition of walls by armoured vehicles crashing through their homes. "They started beating us and telling us to bring out the Britons. We said we didn't have them, but they tied our hands outside and put the women together in one room," said Abu Ali, one of the poverty-stricken Sadr City residents. Police said the raids sparked fighting in which two people had died. The US military said it could not confirm its soldiers' involvement in the search. The British computer expert was seized from a room next to a training centre at the ministry, with bodyguards posted outside. A government employee who witnessed the kidnappings told how two other westerners had narrowly escaped being abducted by the gunmen. One lecturer, believed to be an Irish national, avoided capture after leaving the room to fetch some material only moments before the gunmen entered. A second witness, an Iraqi guard, said the leader of the gunmen was a man in a police major's uniform who spoke in fluent English to the hostages. While Iraqi government officials suggested the kidnappings could have been in retaliation for the killing of the commander of the militia in the southern city of Basra by British-backed Iraqi troops last week, the UK government warned that speculation was not helpful. 'The killing is completely indiscriminate, there's no warning' THE lure of seemingly endless pots of cash for private security firms is not worth the price for one Scottish company owner. Ernie Embleton, a former Royal Marine, pulled his Atlas Security Management team out of Iraq last year, after deciding the situation was just "not worth it". The Ayrshire-based security expert told of his experience setting up and running the Baghdad operation: "It is just plain scary out there now. The situation has just deteriorated so much. All our guys have ex-military experience, but there are now a lot of cowboys operating in Iraq. "We were paying our men up to Â£450 a day, but I have heard of some paying as little as Â£150 - which is peanuts. "Some of them parade around in huge 4x4s, which basically tells everyone you are carrying a foreign client, so you become a target. "We would always be covert, driving around in beaten up old taxis, but ensuring they got safely from A to B. "One day last summer, a car bomb went off and two of our guys were injured, one of them really badly. "That's when we realised how bad it was. They had to wait for three hours to be seen at the hospital, just joining the back of the queue with everyone else. "Then we waited nearly a week to get them airlifted home because we were told that we couldn't use MedEvac. Out there, we also had no back up, or quick reaction force, so you feel quite exposed. "Certainly we had problems in Iraq, we had to bring people home because they didn't want to be there. It is a very intimidating situation. In Iraq, the killing is completely indiscriminate, you have no warning and neither do the civilians. "There are more and more cowboys operating in Iraq. They are unregulated and simply under-cutting the rates. We have moved our operations to Afghanistan now. It is a lot more controlled and not as wide-scale a threat. "Even if we wanted to go back to Iraq, I don't think we would get the guys to do it. It got to the point where we were constantly walking on eggshells. There was nowhere you could feel safe. "It is worse now as the new threat is targeting security companies." Hung Like A Horse , Guga is Jealous / 3:21am 31 May 2007 I'm praying for their safe return. / 8:24am 31 May 2007 Horse... Mare like a Hen... We brought catastrophe on Iraq... make no wonder the natives hit back whenever they get the chance. Save our troops and hostages... Bring them home Now. , paisley / 8:39am 31 May 2007 security lapses???????? ha ha ha This comment has been removed by a moderator. / 9:27am 31 May 2007 "SECURITY experts warned yesterday of serious lapses in intelligence in Iraq" There is very little intelligence in Iraq with Chimpy in charge. There won't be much security either until Iraq is given its own country back, and the neocon invaders leave. That won't be until all the oil is gone; pity so many people have to be murdered so the USA can get their hands on it. David - another one , Edinburgh / 11:01am 31 May 2007 The people of Iraq are rightly proud of their place in the world and long history. Their country was weak after years of sanctions imposed by the UN, sanctions which the people of Iraq could do nothing about. Then foreigners invaded, killing many in the process. They demonstrated utter contempt for the people of Iraq in many ways, including snatching people off the streets in order to torture them. The invaders showed what they were really after by only surrounding the oil ministry after the invasion and ignoring everything else. They introduced new laws to privatise everything in order to hand Iraq on a plate to their financial backers, la