http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/1-4&fd=R&url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30000-1268312,00.html&cid=1116515252&ei=j_1eRtaKJ4e80QGxx5TNDQ Sky News - Relations With Russia At Freezing Point More from Sky News on Channel 501 Relations With Russia At Freezing Point Updated: 14:37, Thursday May 31, 2007 The sensational claims made by the chief suspect in the killing of ex-KGB agent Alexander Litvinenko in London will make relations between Britain and Russia even frostier. Days after extradition papers were served by UK authorities, Andrei Lugovoi said British secret services were involved in his former friend's murder. Worsening relations: Putin and Blair Litvinenko died in a London hospital in November after his tea was poisoned with rare radioactive isotope polonium-210. Mr Lugovoi says the British secret services were involved in his murder - and that his former friend had been working for MI6. Sky News Russia Correspondent Alex Rossi said the claims would intensify the already frosty relations between Britain and Russia. President Vladimir Putin's government has already made clear it has no intention of extraditing Mr Lugovoi. Referring to Mr Lugovoi's press conference, Rossi said: "The language fitted Soviet times rather than the 21st century. "He claimed Alexander Litvinenko had become too much of a nuisance for MI6 and effectively they got rid of him with polonium-210. "He's countering the allegations made against him and the circumstantial evidence of the polonium trail that followed him from Moscow to Britain. "And he's saying that it's not just Russia that has access to polonium-210, but that the poison would have the mark of a Soviet-style assassination and the blame would be batted back to the Kremlin." Mr Lugovoi claimed he had evidence that the British secret services were aware of what was happening even if they did not commit the murder themselves. Rossi added: "There may be a lot of people out there who think this is rubbish but there may also be people who think this has the ring of truth in it. "The key thing is that there are only a few people London who know whether this is true, and only a few people in Moscow who know whether this is true, and all of those people are either not with us any more or in jobs where they are not going to talk about it. "But it certainly ramps up the war of words between London and Moscow." This month Tony Blair himself criticised Russia, drawing attention to Vladimir Putin's energy policy, and saying he had concerns about human rights in Russia. Mr Putin, meanwhile, publicly criticised the UK ambassador to Russia for attending a conference organised by the opposition. To view this content you need Flash and JavaScript enabled in your browser. Please download flash from the Sky Man On View From MI6 Sky's Mark Stone, who met Litvinenko before he was poisoned, speaks to Kay Burley from outside MI6 headquarters in Central London. Watch in video player page KGB Defector Talks To Sky - dur: 01:50 Spy's Friend Accuses Putin Lugovoi Points Finger At MI6 Ex-KGB Man In The Frame Putin: Don't Believe Conspiracies History Of Poison Plots The Trail Of Radiation Litvinenko On His Deathbed The War In Chechnya KGB Suspect Accuses MI6 Madeleine Police 'Frustrated' By Lack Of Progress League Of Their Own: Football Rich Get Richer Search Continues For Kidnapped Brits In Iraq British Soldier Killed In Helicopter 'Attack' More from Sky News: How to get Sky News (pdf) Sky News Library Sales Get Sky News on your site Watch Sky News and Sky News Active on Sky Channel 501 Copyright &copy; 2007 BSkyB
