http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19-5&fd=R&url=http://www.businessdayonline.com/%3Fc%3D45%26a%3D13580&cid=1116809245&ei=j_1eRtaKJ4e80QGxx5TNDQ Shell begins restoring lost 150,000 bpd output Shell begins restoring lost 150,000 bpd output Shell said yesterday it had begun restoring lost production from its Bonny Light oilfields in the country, disrupted after villagers destroyed some of its pipelines. EJIOFOR ALIKE with agency report Angry villagers had for the second time this month attacked a major export pipeline in the country and disrupted 150,000 barrels per day of oil production. Community members stormed the Bomu pipeline complex feeding the Bonny crude export terminal in Rivers State, prompting the partial shutdown of the Trans-Niger pipeline earlier on Tuesday. "We are ramping up production," a company spokeswoman said yesterday. Youths from the K-Dere community started to spill crude oil by opening some pressure indicator valves. Consequently, the company had to shut in some of the oil production. Global crude oil futures were trading higher above $68 yesterday following an early rally on reports of the attack. However, it later slipped below $68 the same day, the fourth straight day of losses due to increased gasoline output by the US. Shell said it had already begun to restore some of the lost production, but would not specify how much. The same protesters, from the Ogoni area of River Stat, had attacked the same pipeline hub on May 10 and occupied it for six days, forcing a 170,000-barrel-a-day closure. "It&#8217;s the same group of boys who occupied the facility last time. They say Shell has broken the agreement it had with them and that&#8217;s why they decided to occupy it again," said Blessing Kolzor, a community leader in K-Dere. The protesters want a stake in the oil flowing through Ogoni, an area where Shell suspended production 14 years ago because of popular protests. There is no production in Ogoni, but the area is still criss-crossed by oil pipelines. Shell had only just resumed normal production levels at its 400,000 bpd Bonny terminal before Tuesday&#8217;s attack. Exports remained under a force majeure, a legal measure exempting Shell from its contractual export obligations. The latest disruption brings to 845,000 bpd, or one-third of capacity, the volume of oil production shut by a wave of unrest in the Niger Delta. President Umaru Yar&#8217;Adua, who took office Tuesday, said he would urgently address the crisis in the oil-producing region. The militants have promised to release six hostages yesterday as a sign of their readiness to talk. However, about 25 foreigners are currently being held captive. Four former governors on the... Nigeria records N889bn private... Yarâ€™Adua vows to tackle... New governors take over... US group to open 100 hotels &copy; BusinessDAY Media Ltd. All Rights Reserved
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/19-3&fd=R&url=http://www.marketwatch.com/news/story/shell-restoring-output-nigeria-bonny/story.aspx%3Fguid%3D%257BC19CCA85-F753-4193-8754-A1AA17E6C6DF%257D&cid=1116809245&ei=j_1eRtaKJ4e80QGxx5TNDQ Shell restoring output at Nigeria Bonny light field - MarketWatch Mutual Funds & ETFs Shell restoring output at Nigeria Bonny light field Last Update: 6:26 AM ET May 30, 2007 LAGOS (MarketWatch) -- Royal Dutch Shell PLC said Wednesday it had begun restoring the 150,000 barrels a day of lost oil production from its Bonny Light field in Nigeria. Protests by youths had partially shut production from the field, according to a Shell spokeswoman in London. "It has been reopened and we are bringing back production," Precious Okolobo, Shell's spokesman in Lagos told Dow Jones Newswires. He said the protesters had closed the Bomu Manifold, a key pipeline hub. Corrected May 30, 2007 07:10 ET (11:10 GMT) The Bonny Light field normally produces around 400,000 barrels of crude oil a day, according to traders. Shell owns 30% of the SPDC joint venture, which operates the site where the attack took place. The state-run National Nigerian Petroleum Corp. owns 55% and units of Total SA (TOT) and Eni SpA (E) hold 10% and 5%, respectively. (Angela Henshall and David Elliott in London contributed to this story.) "It has been reopened and we are bringing back production," Precious Okolobo, Shell's spokesman in Lagos told Dow Jones Newswires. He said the protesters had closed the Bomu Manifold, a key pipeline hub. ("Shell: Restoring Cut Oil Ouput At Nigeria Bonny Light Field," published at 10:08 GMT misstated the Shell spokesman in Lagos' name as Precious Omoku.) Related Blog Posts & Articles U.S. stocks rise amid deal news Wachovia buying A.G. Edwards for $6.8 billion U.S. mortgage rates edge higher for third straight week U.S. GDP revised lower to 0.6% in first quarter Dell seen posting 22% drop in profit as it fights H-P threat Sign up to receive the 