http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-5&fd=R&url=http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/LAC.20070604.G8CLIMATE04/TPStory/Environment&cid=1116969380&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg globeandmail.com: Canada's green record beyond pale Letters to the Editor THE G8 SUMMIT: CARD-CARRYING MEMBERS: THE NEW CLIMATE Canada's green record beyond pale Instead of cutting emissions, country has let them grow by 27 per cent, report says The United States and Canada share the worst records among the G8 countries for dealing with climate change, lagging far behind such leaders as Germany and the United Kingdom, according to a report to be released today by the World Wide Fund for Nature, an international environmental group. Commissioned jointly by WWF and Allianz Group, one of the world's largest insurance companies, the report evaluated measures that the eight major industrialized countries have undertaken to fight climate change, and ranked their relative performance. It's being issued to coincide with the annual G8 summit of Western leaders that starts Wednesday in Germany, where global warming is one of the top agenda items. Among the advanced countries, the report singled out three for their particularly poor records - Canada, the United States, and Russia - saying their policies to fight global warming aren't sufficient to contain the expected rise in the world's temperatures to 2 degrees Celsius. Many scientists predict that if the amount is exceeded, it could lead to catastrophic climate change. &#34;The United States scores the worst of all G8 countries, not having ratified the Kyoto Protocol, nor having put any substantive federal measures in place to curb emissions in the short term,&#34; the report said. &#34;Russia and Canada also have increasing emissions and no policy in place.&#34; Print Edition - Section Front IT TAKES A TOWER The report singled out the Canadian government, led by Prime Minister Stephen Harper, as having &#34;taken up a policy stand, which puts it sharply at odds with its Kyoto obligations as an advanced industrialized country.&#34; Canada also has the poorest record among the G8 when it comes to meeting its Kyoto target to reduce greenhouse gases. Under the pact, Canada needs to cut emissions by 6 per cent from 1990 levels, but they have actually grown 33 per cent above the target, the worst record among the club of the eight rich nations. The United States has also indicated it doesn't want to agree to a G8 statement that would include a commitment to keep warming below the 2-degree danger threshold. Industrialized countries would have to cut emissions by at least 30 per cent by 2020 and then undertake further large reductions - possibly as much as 80 per cent - by 2050 to keep global temperatures from rising more than 2 degrees, according to the report. The report said Italy and Japan have marginally better records than Canada, the United States and Russia, but they do not have the type of policies that are needed if the world is to avoid dangerous warming. Britain, Germany and France are &#34;furthest along&#34; the track toward big emission reductions, it said. Among its other findings, the report said: The United States: It is the world's largest emitter of greenhouse gases, with the highest per capita emissions. The country hasn't ratified Kyoto and hasn't put in place &#34;any substantive federal measures&#34; to curb emissions. Canada: It has a record similar to the United States, with high per capita emissions and &#34;inadequate&#34; mid- to long-term greenhouse-gas-reduction targets. Russia: Emissions declined in the early 1990s, but are now increasing again. The country has &#34;hardly any policy in place to curb emissions.&#34; Britain: Its emissions have met Kyoto requirements, due to a switch from coal as a fuel to gas. Germany: Emissions declined from 1990 to 2000, partly due to the economic collapse of East Germany, but the country has also had a successful program of promoting renewable energy and fosters strong national debate about global warming. Emissions (tonnes of CO2 equivalent per capita) by country, G8 countries in bold. The numbers on the right represent changes in emissions between 1990 and 2004 (* denotes 1990 and 2005). MAGGIE WONG/THE GLOBE AND MAIL Top Stories by Section Brian Mulroney tapped for board seat at Blackstone Rising waters could force hundreds from homes in B.C. U.S. case against Khadr collapses Pronger leaves a hole Paris Hilton begins serving jail sentence On the Web, TV's been a bottom-line blip Living life through the grief Putin threatens to target Europe Harper offers Canada's law as greenhouse template Cutting health tax will put province in debt, McGuinty says Silence of the lamb &#169; Copyright 2007 CTVglobemedia Publishing Inc. All Rights Reserved. The Globe and Mail are divisions of CTVglobemedia Publishing Inc., Submit post to digg.com Seed this post at Newsvine Technorati links to this post
