http://www.forbes.com/business/feeds/afx/2007/06/04/afx3784555.html&cid Israel military court imprisons Hamas ministers for six months - Forbes.com Israel military court imprisons Hamas ministers for six months 06.04.07, 11:02 AM ET BETHLEHEM, West Bank (Thomson Financial) - An Israeli military court ordered today that two Palestinian ministers and a member of parliament from Islamist movement Hamas be held without charge for six months, their lawyers said. The court in northern Israel placed Education Minister Nasseredin al-Shaer, Minister of State Wasfi Qabha and MP Abdelrahman Zeidan in administrative detention for six months, the lawyers said. There was no immediate confirmation from the army of the detention orders against the three politicians, whose arrests drew rare criticism from Israel's key ally, the United States. Administrative detainees can be held without charge for an indefinite period, although their detention orders need periodic renewal by the military courts. The three politicians were arrested along with 31 other senior Hamas officials in the occupied West Bank as part of a crackdown that Israel launched against the Islamist movement nearly three weeks ago in response to increased rocket fire from the Gaza Strip. The US State Department said the arrests of Palestinian elected officials raised 'particular concern', while France condemned the Israeli action. The crackdown on Hamas came as Israel resumed deadly air strikes against the Gaza Strip on May 16 in response to a sharp increase in militant rocket fire from the territory. Last year, the army detained more than 60 Hamas officials, including four ministers, after the group's military wing claimed joint responsibility for the capture of an Israeli soldier in a deadly cross-border raid from Gaza in June, which led to the Israeli bombing of Lebanon. Thirty-nine members of parliament and two former ministers remain in custody from that crackdown. Shaer, who was then deputy prime minister, was also detained in that sweep but a military court ordered him released a month later due to lack of evidence. Copyright AFX News Limited 2007. All rights reserved. The copying, republication or redistribution of AFX News Content, including by framing or similar means, is expressly prohibited without the prior written consent of AFX News. Neither the Subscriber nor AFX News warrants the completeness or accuracy of the Service or the suitability of the Service as a trading aid and neither accepts any liability for losses howsoever incurred. The content on this site, including news, quotes, data and other information, is provided by AFX News and its third party content providers for your personal information only, and neither AFX News nor its third party content providers shall be liable for any errors, inaccuracies or delays in content, or for any actions taken in reliance thereon. More On This Topic ",">"); transformedStoryStr=transformedStoryStr.replaceAll(""","\""); out.write(transformedStoryStr); %--> Starting A Small Business Brought to you by the sponsors below A new book from brings the Himalaya experience home.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/14-3&fd=R&url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/04/asia/AS-GEN-China-Earthquake.php&cid=1116923555&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg Quake displaces tens of thousands in southwest China - International Herald Tribune Subscribe to the newspaper Find out more >> Africa &#038; Middle East Remove all read clippings Quake displaces tens of thousands in southwest China Published: June 4, 2007 Tens of thousands of earthquake victims in southwest China were living in tents or in the open Monday, fearful of returning to their damaged homes a day after a magnitude 6.4 quake killed three and injured at least 300. Hundreds of aftershocks sent jittery residents scurrying for safety. "We worry so much about the aftershocks. This morning we had one, and we hid anyplace we could think of," said Cai Zhongting, who was living with his family in a tent. The quake struck near China&#039;s border with Laos shortly after 5:30 a.m. Sunday (2130 GMT Saturday), said China&#039;s official Xinhua News Agency, citing the government&#039;s seismological bureau. The U.S. Geological Survey measured the quake&#039;s magnitude at 6.2. Xinhua said 20 of the injured were seriously hurt. The dead included a 4-year-old boy who was sleeping with his mother when the mud walls of their home collapsed, burying them, Xinhua said. The mother was later rescued. Today in Asia - Pacific Hong Kong remembers Tiananmen Beijing climate-change strategy has no emission caps Philippine troops defuse bus bomb after U.S. warning Xinhua, citing a provincial civil affairs spokesman, said 120,000 people had been forced to leave their homes. About 20,000 to 30,000 of them were living in tents, some marked "disaster relief," because the earthquake cracked walls in many buildings and made them unsafe to enter, said a man at the Ning&#039;er County Seismological Bureau, who gave only his surname, Ma. Another official from the seismological bureau, who identified himself by his surname, Ye, said others were living without shelter because of a shortage of tents. He said more tents were being sent from other areas. Ma said the local government was providing food and water to displaced residents, although Cai said he and his family &#8212; his wife, 11-year-old daughter and three grandparents &#8212; had to scrounge for supplies themselves in hot, mosquito-infested accommodations. Some businesses opened Monday, including a branch of the Agricultural Bank of China, which was running on generators and providing food and water to six employees, including Cai, who spoke to The Associated Press from the bank. Li Yan, another resident, said she had food but no running water. "My family and I can&#039;t brush our teeth or take showers because of the water shortage. I am drinking mineral water provided by my unit," said Li, reached by telephone at her office. More than 300 aftershocks had been recorded by the local seismic bureau, Xinhua reported, including one with a magnitude of 5.1. Ning&#039;er lies in a quake-prone mountainous region in Yunnan province about 150 kilometers (90 miles) north of Laos, and is famous for its strong tea, known as Pu&#039;er. For centuries, the area sat astride an important trade route for tea and horses that ran along western China between central Asia and southeastern Asia. From 2001 to 2006, Yunnan recorded 27 earthquakes with magnitudes of at least 5.0, Xinhua said. In 1988, a magnitude 7.1 quake in Yunnan near the border with Myanmar killed more than 930 people. More than 15,000 people died after a magnitude 7.7 earthquake in the province in 1970. Meanwhile: I am, therefore I need to dance The four circles of a changing world Speakers bureaus give book authors a new income stream Beijing climate-change strategy has no emission caps 3 mild earthquakes rattle New Hampshire Drug may be first effective medication for liver cancer Hear the first victims of climate change Russia says it will target European sites if U.S. missile 