al or investigation," Putin said in the interview ahead of this week's summit of the Group of Eight (G-8) industrial nations. "Look what's going on in Europe: the harsh treatment of demonstrators, the use of rubber bullets, tear gas in one capital or another, the killing of demonstrators in the streets." He also attacked post-Soviet Ukraine for "completely violating the constitution and all its laws" and heading for "complete tyranny" -- an apparent reference to the political deadlock between rival factions over the calling of fresh elections. "After the death of Mahatma Gandhi there's nobody to talk to," he concluded, referring to the Indian leader who championed civil rights and non-violent resistance to tyranny. Asked whether there was any move in Russia towards a return to totalitarian rule, Putin simply said: "That is complete rubbish, don't believe that." &copy; Reuters 2007. All rights reserved. Editors Choice: Best pictures from the last 24 hours. Notes by Napoleon, Churchill found in laundry room Tiananmen Square, 18 years later" /> Tiananmen Square, 18 years later Feeling blue? Study says marriage might cheer you up START News Content Page Tags 'Text' | 'Picture' | 'Slideshow' | 'Video' ie. headline for article ie. headline for article END News Content Page Tags Thousands of revellers take part in one of Bolivia's most important festivals, the Feast of the Lord of Great Power. Iran president sees "countdown" to Israel's end I'm the world's only true democrat, says Putin Hustler offers $1 million for sex smut on Congress Iraq Qaeda group says killed captured U.S. troops DUBAI (Reuters) - An al Qaeda-led group in Iraq signaled in a Web video on Monday that it had killed three U.S. soldiers after capturing them last month, showing only pictures of ID cards of two missing U.S. soldiers. Loews bets on natural gas in $4 billion Dominion deal Paris Hilton begins jail term a day early Strikers have new gripe--no sex Apple says iPhone to go on sale June 29 Watch th