http://www.ft.com/cms/s/f57701b6-1286-11dc-a475-000b5df10621.html&cid FT.com / World - 'Garbage jobs' stifle Spanish innovation Skip to main content, accesskey 's' Subscribe to FT.com or view and edit your subscription details. All times are London time Search News in the FT.com site Search Quotes in the FT.com site Buenos Aires freeze brings energy disarray Protest at ChÃ¡vezâ€™s TV clampdown Uribe asks US not to punish Colombia Economy boosts Kirchner amid poll concerns TV channel axed in latest ChÃ¡vez drama Ex-senator takes fight to Mexicoâ€™s networks Launch set for Latin America bank Brazil energy minister resigns over scandal Mexico hit by drug-fuelled wave of terror TelefÃ³nica joins battle for Brazil bonanza 'Garbage jobs' stifle Spanish innovation Published: October 21 2005 03:00 | Last updated: October 21 2005 03:00 Alex Drajicevic expected a good job when he arrived in Spain from Chile more than 10 years ago. With a degree in economics, he assumed it would be easy to find in a country with a booming economy. But the only employment available was poorly paid, short-term work that offered little security and few benefits - what the Spanish call "garbage jobs". As a result, he has spent 10 years chasing the elusive permanent work contract while working with "definite", or temporary, contracts in call centres, earning between â‚¬800 and â‚¬1,300 ($1,560, Â£883) a month. Mr Drajicevic is not alone. Non-existent before a series of labour market reforms in the 1990s, temporary and single-assignment contracts now cover more than 35 per cent of all jobs in Spain, against a European average of 12 per cent. Of the 900,000 jobs created in Spain in the year to June, two-thirds carry contracts of six months or less. The widespread use of temporary contracts has helped the country more than halve its official unemployment rate since the 1993 recession, to 9.3 per cent. It also partly explains - along with campaigns to bring the underground job market into the open - a 60 per cent increase in the number of people in work over the same period. Despite that success, Spaniards remain ambivalent about the benefits. The ability to shift from a temporary to a permanent contract appears to depend more on personal contacts than on the merit of one's work. The relative insecurity of "definite" contracts also undermines the concept of the breadwinner protecting his or her nuclear family - a cultural tenet particularly strong in Spain and in Italy - where "definite" contracts are also proliferating amid great distrust. Economists in Spain also worry that the trend towards temporary working is stifling innovation and worker mobility, and is part of the reason for Spain's poor productivity rates relative to the rest of Europe. Temporary contracts offer little, if any, training and pay as little as â‚¬4 an hour, locking a whole new class of Spaniards and immigrants into life without prospects. Some experts also argue that the job insecurity leads to a lack of enterprise among young people with university degrees. Although Spanish scientists account for 4 per cent of the world's published research, the country lags behind most of Europe in innovation league tables based on patent filing. As a whole, Spanish companies spend less than half the European average on research and development. "The precariousness of the job market means many youngsters are looking for security above all else," says Juan Carlos MartÃ­nez, an economist at the Instituto de Empresa business school in Madrid. "It frightens me to see a whole generation of youngsters aspiring to be civil servants." Large companies, in particular, are often accused of abusing temporary contracts. Contracts often run until the end of July, the start of the holiday season, and then are renewed in September, when Spaniards return to work, so that employers avoid having to pay for holidays. Employers, however, blame the costs of hiring and firing in Spain. Their share of social security contributions, as a percentage of wages, is among the highest in Europe. Employees dismissed or made redundant are often entitled to 45 days' pay for every year worked, compared with a maximum of eight in the UK. "Spain can't advance in the area of labour flexibility until we lower the costs of dismissal and social security contributions," says Sandalio Go'mez of the IESE business school in Barcelona. Under pressure by both labour unions and the corporate sector, the socialist government of Jose' Luis Rodriguez Zapatero has proposed making it easier to dismiss workers on indefinite contracts, while improving conditions for those in temporary jobs. Guillermo de la Dehesa, a leading economist, says Spain needs to find the right mix of labour flexibility and worker incentives to promote productivity. "People on fixed-term contracts need to become a little less secure to give more security to those on short-term contracts". The Financial Times Limited 2007 - create a keyword alert on the subject of this topic - download our application to receive instant alerts on this topic - start your day with daily email briefing on this topic - Track this news topic using our feeds "Middle East" sub navigation "By sector" sub navigation "By region" sub navigation "Markets headlines" sub navigation "Market data" sub navigation Australia & New Zealand "Managed funds" sub navigation "Comment & Analysis" sub navigation Comment & Analysis main "Debates and polls" sub navigation Debates and polls main "Video & Audio" sub navigation Video & Audio main View from the Top "Business Life" sub navigation "Business education" sub navigation Features of the week "Your Money" sub navigation "Advice & comment" sub navigation Advice & comment main "Compare & apply" sub navigation Compare & apply main "Arts & Weekend" sub navigation Arts & Weekend main How to spend it "Weekend columnists" sub navigation "In depth" sub navigation "Special Reports" sub navigation Future of Europe 2007 "Jobs & classified" sub na