lestinians are also restricted by more than 500 checkpoints and blockades as well as a road network reserved for Israelis. The policies are aimed at benefiting "continuously expanding but unlawful Israeli settlements" while causing the "virtual collapse of the Palestinian economy," Amnesty charged. They are also "exacerbating the increasingly fragile conditions in which Palestinians live and work - resulting in levels of despair, poverty and food insecurity never before seen in the territories," Smart said. "Most Palestinians are now relying on aid for subsistence, with families reducing the quality and quantity of the food they consume and selling assets essential for their livelihoods." Israeli actions, Amnesty said, have "resulted in widespread human rights abuses and have also failed to bring security to the Israeli and Palestinian civilian populations." Amnesty called on Israel to lift the blockades and other restrictions and ensure its actions target specific threats rather than punish communities. It also urged Israel to stop building the barrier inside the West Bank, scrap all settlements and end its policy of demolishing Palestinian homes. Amnesty repeated calls for armed Palestinian groups to stop attacking Israeli civilians and for Palestinian authorities to prosecute those that did. It called too on the UN or another body to deploy an "international human rights monitoring mechanism" to get Israelis and Palestinians to comply with obligations under international law. Israeli and Palestinian peace groups are staging demonstrations this week to protest at 40 years of occupation following the 1967 Six Day War. The events run from today until Sunday, marking the anniversary of a war that saw Israel capture East Jerusalem and the West Bank from Jordan, the Gaza Strip and Sinai from Egypt and Golan Heights from Syria. AGENCE FRANCE-PRESSE &copy; 2007 The Standard, The Standard Newspapers Publishing Ltd. Trademark and Copyright Notice: Copyright 2005, The Stand