s would have on the civilian population. Mr Taylor has denied the charges. The prosecution alleges Mr Taylor, who led his own rebellion in Liberia in the 1990s, was a key player in the regional conflict, marked by mass killings, mutilations and rapes. But any hopes that the latest exercise in international justice would prove smoother than the trials of other former heads of state â€“ notably Slobodan Milosevic and Saddam Hussein â€“ were dashed amid the confusion. When the day's proceedings ended, Judge Sebutinde acknowledged Mr Taylorâ€™s complaints, saying "there has to be some equality of armsâ€ and ordered adequate facilities be provided "without further delay". The trial is being conducted by the Special Court for Sierra Leone, an ad hoc tribunal established to try perpetrators of the worst atrocities committed in the country after November 1996. The trial had already been expected to adjourn for a few weeks after yesterday's opening, to allow the defence more time to prepare. That time may now be deployed in trying to sort out the defenceâ€™s problems. The Financial Times Limited 2007 "Middle East" sub navigation "By sector" sub navigation "By region" sub navigation "Markets headlines" sub navigation "Market data" sub navigation Australia & New Zealand "Managed funds" sub navigation "Comment & Analysis" sub navigation Comment & Analysis main "Debates and polls" sub navigation Debates and polls main "Video & Audio" sub navigation Video & Audio main View from the Top "Business Life" sub navigation "Business education" sub navigation Features of the week "Your Money" sub navigation "Advice & comment" sub navigation Advice & comment main "Compare & apply" sub navigation Compare & apply main "Arts & Weekend" sub navigation Arts & Weekend main How to spend it "Weekend columnists" sub navigation "In depth" sub navigation "Special Reports" sub navigation Future of Europe 2007 "Jobs & classified" sub navigation Jobs & classified main "Services & tools" sub navigation 