http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/15-1&fd=R&url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi%3Ffile%3D/chronicle/archive/2007/06/04/EDGGTP3DAN1.DTL&cid=1116197449&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg 40th Anniversary of the Six-Day War / Solution on which all agree impossible to achieve Solution on which all agree impossible to achieve" /> 40th Anniversary of the Six-Day War Solution on which all agree impossible to achieve Monday, June 4, 2007 Letters to the Editor Forty years ago this week, Israel conquered the West Bank and Gaza Strip, re-establishing a political system in which one sovereign ruled over all of former Palestine. Unnoticed by the world, this brought about a version of a "single state solution" to the Palestinian-Israeli conflict -- albeit one in which Palestinians and Jews do not have equal rights. Instead, Israel has ruled the West Bank and Gaza Strip through military governments that control the daily lives of millions of Palestinians in every aspect, yet in which they have no say. Although Palestinians now elect representatives to a Palestinian Authority, these officials administer the tiny Gaza Strip, and less than 20 percent of the West Bank. Their powers scarcely exceed those of county supervisors. Meanwhile, international opinion has steadily solidified behind a "two state solution." In this scenario, independent Jewish and Palestinian states would divide the land between the Mediterranean coast and the River Jordan. By the mid-1970s, most states in the U.N. General Assembly supported Palestinian nationhood. In 1988, the PLO explicitly recognized Israel within its pre-1967 borders, agreeing to sovereignty over the West Bank and Gaza Strip, together comprising just 22 percent of former Palestine. The United States finally joined the bandwagon in 2002, when President Bush called for two democratic states living side by side in his "Roadmap to Peace." Even Israel has signed on, although its conception of what territory and powers a Palestinian state should possess is more constrictive than anyone else's. Ironically, this unanimity, so laboriously assembled over decades, upholds a solution that is now impossible to achieve. Israel's program of colonizing the West Bank has become irreversible, and the land base for a viable Palestinian state has disappeared. Some 450,000 Israeli settlers now occupy more than 140 settlements in East Jerusalem and the West Bank. These Jewish settlements, the security swaths around them, the roads linking them to each other and to Israel, and the "separation wall" that pens Palestinians into discontiguous islands of land, cover more than 40 percent of the West Bank. Much of this is either private Palestinian property, seized without compensation, or state lands in which Palestinians hold traditional use rights that Israel refuses to respect. Meanwhile, Israel's colonizing juggernaut rolls ahead. Recently, plans to build 2,500 new homes for Israeli settlers east of Jerusalem were announced, and orders were given to continue construction of the "separation wall" in the Jordan Valley. There appears to be no political force capable of slowing, let alone halting, this movement. A comforting illusion has been fostered that if Palestinians and Israelis could only be coaxed back into negotiations, the elusive two-state solution would somehow materialize. The interests of leaders on all sides are served by this fiction, although for different reasons. For President Bush, an appearance of progress toward Palestinian-Israeli peace quells hostility toward the United States in the Middle East, and eases policy options elsewhere in the region, including Iraq. The PLO leadership, personified in the hapless Mahmoud Abbas, staked its entire political legitimacy in the Oslo accords and the endless "peace process" it inaugurated. Abandoning negotiations toward a two-state solution would constitute an admission that it had led the Palestinians into a terrible dead-end. Israel mollifies the United States by engaging in the negotiation charade, exploits the continuing indeterminacy to continue colonizing the West Bank, and advances its strategic objective of permanent control over most or all of former Palestine. Like the shimmering waters of a desert mirage, the two-state solution moves just out of reach with every apparent advancing step. The tragedy is that temporizing in the face of this inevitable truth ultimately serves neither Israeli Jews, nor Palestinian Arabs, nor Americans. Continued conflict in the region hurts the direct parties in obvious ways, and also deeply undermines the status of the United States in the Arab and Muslim worlds. Our reflexive support of Israel, even in its self-destructive policies, is a prime cause of hostility against us. The number of Israeli Jews and Palestinian Arabs living within the borders of former Palestine are now roughly equivalent, at just more than 5 million each. The question is: Will political power within this single political system continue to be exercised in what former ANC member and current South African Intelligence Minister Ronnie Kasrils and others have described as an acute form of apartheid? Or will Palestinian Arabs and Israeli Jews enjoy equal rights and share power fairly in what is already a joint polity? For those who support peace, justice and respect for international law, the choice should be obvious. George Bisharat is a professor of law at Hastings College of the Law, and writes frequently on law and politics in the Middle East. This article appeared on page Get up to 50% off home delivery of the Chronicle for 12 weeks! Garbage truck backs up, kills Sausalito restaurant employee Familiar name back on city payroll with new job Enhanced romance The G-Shot -- Is it the latest panacea to improve your... No explanation yet for why Southwest jet&#x27;s landing gear collapsed 2 hospitalized in SoMa stabbing Paris Hilton Checks Into L.A. Jail THE BADGE The two cops who know all the gang members Enhanced romance The G-Shot -- Is it the latest panacea to improve your... THE NIGHTMARE OF GETTING THERE Surge in applications has created a... ON THE JOB Quitters sometimes win: Jumping ship in order to clean them Southwest flight&#x27;s gear collapses on landing at Oakland airport SAN FRANCISCO Woman hit and killed in crosswalk on 19th Ave. IN JOHN MUIR&#x27;S FOOTSTEPS Santa Cruz couple retrace famed naturalist&#x27;s 1868... Familiar name back on city payroll with new job THE BADGE The two cops who know all the gang members &#x27;No intention of resigning,&#x27; vows S.F. Supervisor Ed Jew Guantanamo Judge Dismisses Terror Case Polish Girl&#x27;s Holocaust Diary Unveiled Indiana Kangaroo Dies After Capture Deputies arrest man after Dana Point knife attacks E. coli fear spurs ground beef recall at Albertsons, Save-A-Lot SOS Security Inc . Immediate OF CALIFORNIA DEPARTMENT OF Sales Manager Will train right RN CASE MANAGER Chinese Community if you are looking for a modern San Mateo County Office of Education 1000 HIRING BONUS Deliver small The California Dept. of Corrections & Rehab. Not just a career, but a way of life. City of Walnut Creek Office. SF, B.A . in management FABRICATION Layout - Custom Sheet View All Top Jobs &copy; 2007 Hearst Communications Inc.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.metimes.com/storyview.php%3FStoryID%3D20070603-033705-6385r&cid=1116516999&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg Clashes erupt at Lebanon camp - Region - Middle East Times Monday, Jun 04 2007 Clashes erupt at Lebanon camp FIGHTING CONTINUES: A shell explodes as smoke rises from the Palestinian Nahr Al Bared refugee camp in northern Lebanon June 2, 2007. Sporadic fighting erupted again between the army and Islamist gunmen Sunday. NAHR AL BARED, Lebanon -- The thud of shelling and the rattle of machinegun fire reverberated around a Palestinian camp in Lebanon Sunday as sporadic fighting erupted again between the army and Islamist gunmen. The clashes followed the heaviest bouts of gunbattles since the deadly standoff between besieging government forces and the Al Qaeda inspired Fatah Al Islam militia began in northern Lebanon two weeks ago. As tanks encircled the squalid Nahr Al Bared refugee camp, Prime Minister Fuad Siniora warned Saturday that the militants holed up inside must surrender or be wiped out. "This is a terrorist gang," Siniora said in an interview with Al Arabiya television. "They have to surrender themselves and their arms." He said if the Islamists give up "they will face a fair trial," but added that the army was carrying out missions against the Nahr Al Bared camp "like surgical operations in order to eradicate this phenomenon." But Fatah Al Islam, a tiny band of Sunni Muslim extremists, vowed it would fight to the last man. In all 95 people have been killed since May 20, including 42 soldiers and 41 Islamist gunmen, in the bloodiest internal fighting in Lebanon since the 1975 to 1990 civil war. Siniora said the camp's population had fallen from more than 31,000 to fewer than 3,000, including the gunmen, after civilians fled the fighting and an increasingly desperate humanitarian situation. He accused Fatah Al Islam, which he said had about 250 men, of preventing remaining civilians from leaving the camp in an apparent bid to use them as human shields. Fatah Al Islam spokesman Abu Salim Taha vowed: "We will not surrender and we will fight until the last drop of blood. "The Nahr Al Bared camp will not fall despite the destructive shelling, and the army will not be able to enter," Taha said. On Saturday, troops pounded Nahr Al Bared with 155mm artillery fire, an Agence France Presse correspondent said. Batteries of big guns on high ground targeted the northwest of Nahr Al Bared, where most of the militants were believed to be entrenched. Two helicopters also used heavy machine guns, the first time choppers have been used in the battle. An Agence France Presse photographer said the helicopters made about a dozen passes above positions manned by Fatah Al Islam, which replied with anti-tank rockets without hitting either aircraft. Sheikh Mohammed Al Hajj, a member of a delegation of Palestinian clerics attempting to broker a negotiated solution, called for a halt to the shelling. But the Islamist Hamas movement of Palestinian Prime Minister Ismail Haniya said the "tangible progress" made by the army in clearing the camp's northern and eastern edges of militants might help mediation efforts. "This is a victory that could open the way for a political settlement," spokesman Ali Baraka said. An army spokesman said "our soldiers have cleaned up pockets of resistance around the north and east sides of the camp, and sappers have made safe buildings booby-trapped by Fatah Al Islam on the edges of the camp before they can be dislodged." A mainstream Palestinian commander inside the camp said at least eight militants had been killed Friday, but that there were no casualties among civilians, as they were sheltering in areas under his control. "Southern districts have been completely spared bombardment by the Lebanese army - that's why there have been no victims among civilians," said Abu Imad Halwani, regional commander of the Fatah movement of Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas. Halwani said his men were building a sand barrier across the center of the camp to "prevent the Fatah Al Islam fighters from slipping in among the civilian population to escape the army siege." He also said the trapped residents, whom he numbered at 5,000, were running out of food and water. Halwani said the encircling troops have "not entered the camp, but have been besieging it from the north and the east," supporting the army's repeated insistence that its forces have remained outside Nahr Al Bared. By longstanding convention, the army does not enter Lebanon's 12 Palestinian refugee camps, leaving security inside to militant groups. The International Committee of the Red Cross called on all parties not to target civilians. Missing US soldiers' IDs posted in video online Nine rebels, soldier killed in Afghanistan Israel rejects Amnesty criticism over barrier EU presses Turkey to pursue reforms UAE grants amnesty to illegal workers UAE's Abraaj buys Egypt's EFC for $1.41bn Analysis: At odds with US over Iraq oil Israeli police okay Gay Pride parade in Jerusalem Six days that changed the face of the Middle East Greenpeace builds an ark in Turkey Muslim hardliners storm Indonesia church Central Africa sex abuse continues, says UN UAE minister launches her own perfume Israeli FM with senior Palestinian calls for peace Husband of jailed Iranian-American pleads for her freedom Lithuania probes anti-gay Web site Telecommuters tap into office work revolution Microsoft adds copyrighted books to online library 'AIDS cure' in Zambia found to be pesticide Review of Arab Editorials Review of Arab Editorials Commentary: Robert Kennedy's legacy Commentary: Hopes high for Lebanon tribunal It's an Odd World! London unveils logo for 2012 Olympics Britain to boost funding to promote moderate Islam Greece to reclaim stolen artifacts from US museum Polo Beach Wailea; Lake Tahoe rentals Laantec Hardware PC Shop Copyright &copy; 2007 News World Communications Inc.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-4&fd=R&url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ap/world/4860226.html&cid=1116948212&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg Tiananmen Square survivors seek reform | Chron.com - Houston Chronicle " width="11" height="11" border="0"> Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Travel News & Features Legal & Public Notices " width="9" height="10" vsapce="1" border="0"> June 4, 2007, 2:19PM Tiananmen Square survivors seek reform By ANITA CHANG Associated Press Writer &copy; 2007 The Associated Press BEIJING &mdash; For the first time in 18 years, Ding Zilin marked the anniversary of her son's death with a visit to the place where he was shot amid a violent government crackdown on protests at Tiananmen Square. Police usually are quick to snuff out any memorials in Beijing for those killed in the crackdown that culminated in June 4, 1989, while China's government still calls the seven-week Tiananmen protest a counter-revolutionary riot and has yet to fully disclose what happened. But with China's human rights record under renewed scrutiny ahead of the 2008 Olympics, survivors of the bloody crackdown in Beijing marked the event's 18th anniversary on Monday by demanding political reform. And Ding, who for years was placed under house arrest during Tiananmen anniversaries and other sensitive times, wept on the eve of the anniversary as she placed a photo of her son on the spot where he died a few kilometers west of Tiananmen. "It's been 18 years and I felt like I let him down and let down the others who died with him," she said of her son, who was killed as he hid behind a flower bed from soldiers enforcing martial law on the night of June 3. He had turned 17 the day before. In Hong Kong on Monday &mdash; the only place in China where a large, public commemoration is allowed &mdash; tens of thousands gathered to mourn the dead at a candlelight vigil. In Beijing's Tiananmen Square, there were no immediate reports of protests and only tourists gathered to watch a daily flag-raising ceremony amid tight security. Ding, co-founder of the Tiananmen Mothers, a group that represents families of those who died, said police did not try to stop her Sunday night, though plainclothes agents may have been observing the vigil. "Right now, this is all I can do. Not getting justice for them, we're still pushing for it but there's been no response," said Ding, who has campaigned to get the government to acknowledge those killed in the crackdown and compensate their families. "Their spirits are obviously not at peace." Most of the surviving students who led the Tiananmen protests have drifted away from activism and into careers in business or other professions, but prominent student leader Wang Dan has continued to push for political reform in China as he pursues a doctorate in history at Harvard University. He said in a videotaped message that China's recent economic success cannot make up for the crackdown and killed hundreds, maybe thousands, of people. "Who can guarantee things that happened 18 years ago will not happen 18 years later?" Wang said. "Even if we become more powerful economically, China still cannot rise in international society." Another former student leader, Wu'er Kaixi, lamented that the memory of Tiananmen appears to be fading worldwide. "The Chinese government is unwilling to face the truth and seems to hope that the 'problem' of June 4 will simply go away," Wu'er, who has worked as a businessman and radio broadcaster in Taiwan, told The Associated Press. "For the most part, the world seems willing to go along with this." In the former British colony of Hong Kong, many residents in 1989 supported the Tiananmen protesters and the violence raised fears that the Communist leadership would not honor its promise to allow Hong Kong the civil liberties its people enjoyed under British rule. But 10 years after the hand-over, the city still enjoys freedoms that people on the mainland can only dream about. Street protests are common and the press frequently criticizes the government, though media watchdogs say self-censorship is common. A candlelight vigil Monday night filled up six soccer fields at Victoria Park near downtown Hong Kong. Amy Chan, 60, brought her 5-year-old granddaughter. "Although she is young, we need to let her know the history," Chan said. Tonny Chin, 50, a clerk, said he has attended the vigil every year since 1989. "The June fourth incident is a tragedy for China," he said. "We need to vindicate it." New York-based Human Rights Watch said Beijing's failure to account for the crackdown casts a pall on its campaign to project a new image ahead of the Olympics in 14 months. "Beijing &mdash; and by extension, the 2008 Olympic Games &mdash; will remain tarnished by this legacy until the Chinese government provides a complete and truthful account of what happened in June 1989," said Sophie Richardson, deputy Asia director of the human rights group. Associated Press writers Dikky Sinn and William Foreman in Hong Kong and Annie Huang in Taipei, Taiwan, contributed to this report. Australian remains in Vietnam head home 1,683 guitarists play 'Smoke on Water' Egypt: No to ancient pyramids on stamp France sets quotas for immigrant arrests Indonesian kangaroos to gain freedom Silva proposes forest preservation plan Landslide damages famed valley in Russia Survivors mark anniversary of Tiananmen Square crackdown Company to Create Chinese Virtual World Company to Create Chinese Virtual World Forbes' billionaires by country Huang Ju, 68, was Chinese vice premier Key China official Huang Ju dies List of the world's richest people Forbes' billionaires by rank Most Asian Markets Rise Despite Shanghai Forbes' list of the world's billionaires Buy Photos & Page Prints 2005-Present Historic Page Prints 1901-2004 Copyright Notice & Privacy Policy
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/12-5&fd=R&url=http://english.people.com.cn/200706/04/eng20070604_380611.html&cid=1116909385&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg People's Daily Online -- Where are food queues, asks man after 19-year coma China at a glance China in brief 2004 CPC & state organs Selected Works of Deng Xiaoping UPDATED: 15:53, June 04, 2007 Where are food queues, asks man after 19-year coma Jan Grzebskia holds his wife Gertruda Grzebska's hand as they pose for the photographer at their apartment in Dzialdowo, 160 km (100 miles) north from Warsaw, June 3, 2007. has awoken after a 19-year coma to discover a completely different world. Jan Grzebski, 65, was hit by a train in 1988 and was given only two years to live by doctors. But his wife Gertruda continued to care for him, and never lost hope that he would recover consciousness. Grzebski, a father of four from Dzialdowo, northern Poland, who remains confined to a wheelchair, was in his mid-40s when he slipped into the coma. Now that he has regained consciousness, however, he has observed that the dramatic transformation of the Polish economy and the invention of modern technologies such as the mobile phone appears to have done little to cheer his countrymen up. He had been living under president Wojciech Jaruzelski's regime of food shortages, and queues for petrol in a country which was almost completely cut off from the West by the Iron Curtain. "When I went into a coma there was only tea and vinegar in the shops, meat was rationed and huge petrol queues were everywhere," he told the Polish news channel TVN24. "Now I see people on the streets with cell phones and there are so many goods in the shops it makes my head spin. What amazes me is all these people who walk around with their mobile phones and never stop moaning - I've got nothing to complain about." Since he fell into his coma, Grzebski's children have all grown up, married and together have given him 11 grandchildren, whom he saw for the first time when he awoke. He told family members that he had vague memories of family gatherings with his close relatives talking to him. His most lavish praise was reserved for his wife, who had for 19 years tended his every need, turning her husband in his bed every hour to prevent sores. "It was Gertruda who saved me, and I'll never forget it," added Grzebski. Polish doctors who had been monitoring his progress agreed. Dr Boguslaw Poniatowski said: "For 19 years Mrs Grzebski did the job of an experienced intensive care team, changing her comatose husband's position every hour to prevent bed-sore infections." Gertruda said: 'I cried a lot, and I prayed a lot. Those who came to see us kept asking: 'When is he going to die?' But he's not dead." Comment on the story Copyright by People's Daily Online, all rights reserved
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-6&fd=R&url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/06/04/europe/EU-GEN-Serbia-War-crimes.php&cid=1116579515&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg UN war crimes prosecutor pushes for handover of Mladic, other suspects - International Herald Tribune Subscribe to the newspaper Find out more >> Africa &#038; Middle East Remove all read clippings UN war crimes prosecutor pushes for handover of Mladic, other suspects Published: June 4, 2007 The chief U.N. war crimes prosecutor for the former Yugoslavia on Monday pressed for the capture of war crimes suspects as Serbia announced plans to unearth another mass grave of the victims of Slobodan Milosevic&#039;s regime in the 1990s. Carla Del Ponte met government leaders and security officials, demanding the handover of five Serb suspects still at large, notably Gen. Ratko Mladic. The wartime Bosnian Serb military commander is charged with genocide in the slaughter of more than 7,000 Bosnian Muslims in Srebrenica in 1995 &#8212; the worst single atrocity in Europe since World War II. Meanwhile, Serbian war crimes prosecutors said they will exhume a a mass grave that is believed to contain up to 500 Albanian victims of the Kosovo war &#8212; more evidence of Milosevic&#039;s crackdown against Kosovo&#039;s majority in 1999 as the U.N. debates whether to grant statehood to the independence-seeking province. The exhumation will be held Tuesday at an abandoned quarry in no man&#039;s land between Serbia and Kosovo. This would be the third mass grave containing the victims of Milosevic&#039;s crackdown against independence-seeking Kosovo Albanians during the 1998-99 war there. About 800 bodies were discovered in the other two mass graves discovered since 2000 in Serbia. Del Ponte&#039;s four-day visit came days after one of Mladic&#039;s top aides during the 1992-95 Bosnian war, Gen. Zdravko Tolimir, was arrested near the Serbian-Bosnian border. Tolimir was transferred to the U.N. tribunal in The Hague, Netherlands, and made an initial appearance before the court later Monday where he refused to enter a plea. G-8 quandary: Dealing with Putin How long before Bush pushes Russia back? Putin says British calls for Lugovoi extradition &#x27;stupidity&#x27; Tolimir complained that international laws were breached in his arrest and extradition, which he said took place in his "native country" of Serbia without opportunity to consult a lawyer &#8212; and not in Bosnia, as Serb authorities have contended. This was another sign that the Serbian authorities were still reluctant to arrest war crimes suspects, apparently fearing backlash from ultranationalists who consider them war heroes. Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said in a statement after meeting Del Ponte that Serbia has the "political will and determination" to capture the remaining war crimes fugitives "soonest." Del Ponte, according to the government statement, told Kostunica that the tribunal "seeks full Serbia&#039;s cooperation so that all the accused suspects find themselves in The Hague." The European Union last year suspended pre-membership talks with Serbia after Belgrade failed to meet two deadlines for Mladic to be extradited to The Hague. The suspension was a result of a negative report to the U.N. Security Council from Del Ponte about Serbia&#039;s cooperation with the tribunal, but EU officials have suggested recently that negotiations could resume. Del Ponte&#039;s next report is due in a few weeks. On Sunday the EU&#039;s enlargement commissioner, Olli Rehn, said, "On the basis of a very careful and extensive assessment ... we can start these talks in early June." Still, the actual signing of the Stabilization and Association Agreement with Serbia &#8212; a stepping stone to possible membership &#8212; is likely to take place only after Mladic is in the tribunal&#039;s custody. Serbia&#039;s government has changed since Del Ponte&#039;s last visit in October. But Kostunica, whom Del Ponte has repeatedly accused of failing to meet promises to arrest suspects, remains in office. The new Cabinet includes members of the pro-Western Democratic Party, led by President Boris Tadic, who has made it a priority to find the suspects and unblock Serbia&#039;s path to EU membership. Del Ponte&#039;s mandate as the chief U.N. war crimes prosecutor for the former Yugoslavia expires in September. Meanwhile: I am, therefore I need to dance The four circles of a changing world Speakers bureaus give book authors a new income stream Beijing climate-change strategy has no emission caps 3 mild earthquakes rattle New Hampshire Drug may be first effective medication for liver cancer Hear the first victims of climate change Russia says it will target European sites if U.S. missile shield proceeds Inmates say Paris Hilton is in for a stay in &#39;hell&#39; Commanders say push in Baghdad is short of goal U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; Corruption in China: The anger boils over Chinese drug commissioner is sentenced to death Understanding and coping with tremors An escapee tells of life and death in North Korea&#39;s labor camps Malaysia rejects Muslim convert&#39;s bid to be recognized as Christian A rare glimpse of 19th-century Iran With allies in enemy ranks, GIs in Iraq are no longer true believers Genes take charge, and diets fall by the wayside U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Tracing a poison&#39;s global path back to China Jet lag: How to make the best of a bad situation Do not neglect culture In Estonia, what may be the first war in cyberspace Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy The assault on Assyrian Christians No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; IHT.com on the go Listen to IHT articles on your computer, and create custom podcasts for your portable music