http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/3-1&fd=R&url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2007-06/04/content_6192912.htm&cid=1116833452&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg Seven more U.S. soldiers killed in Iraq Tension escalates in Iraq ¡¤Seven more U.S. soldiers have been killed in multiple attacks across Iraq. ¡¤So far, at least 16 U.S. soldiers have been killed in Iraq this month. ¡¤The U.S. death toll rises to 3,494 since the outbreak of U.S.-led invasion to Iraq in 2003. BAGHDAD, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Seven more U.S. soldiers have been killed in multiple attacks across Iraq, including four in a roadside bombing, U.S. military said on Sunday. The four died on Sunday while conducting a combined cordon and search operation northwest of the capital, a military statement said. Two other soldiers were killed and five were wounded along with an Iraqi interpreter in two separate roadside bombings in Baghdad on Sunday, according to military statements. Another soldier was killed on Saturday in a roadside bombing while conducting combat operation in western Baghdad, a military statement said, adding eight other soldiers were wounded. Earlier Sunday, the military announced deaths of seven U.S. soldiers on Saturday. So far, at least 16 U.S. soldiers have been killed in Iraq this month, bringing the U.S. death toll to more than 3,494 since the outbreak of U.S.-led invasion to Iraq in 2003. Six U.S. soldiers killed in Iraq on Saturday BAGHDAD, June 3 (Xinhua) -- Two more U.S. soldiers were killed in northern Iraq on Saturday, bringing the death toll to six in insurgents' attacks across Iraq, the U.S. military said on Sunday. Two soldiers were killed in a roadside bomb attack near their patrol during operations in the northern Nineveh province, the military said in a statement. U.S. defense chief envisions long-term military presence in Iraq WASHINGTON, May 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary Robert Gates said Thursday that he envisions some level of American troops in Iraq for a "protracted period of time," possibly under a South Korea-like security arrangement and with the agreement of the Iraqi government. "What I'm thinking in terms of is a mutual agreement where some force of Americans -- mutually agreed with mutually agreed missions -- is present for a protracted period of time," Gates said in Hawaii, where he was visiting the U.S. Pacific Command in Hawaii on the way to security talks in Singapore. Six U.S. soldiers killed in Iraq on Saturday U.S. defense chief envisions long-term military presence in Iraq U.S. elite forces carry out up to 12 raids in Iraq each night Six U.S. soldiers killed in bomb attack in Iraq U.S., Iran to hold rare Iraq talks
