http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.voanews.com/english/2007-06-04-voa42.cfm&cid=1116579515&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg VOA News - Survivors of 1995 Srebrenica Massacre File Suit Against Netherlands, UN A trusted source of news and information since 1942 Survivors of 1995 Srebrenica Massacre File Suit Against Netherlands, UN From left: Dutch lawyers Axel Hagedorn and Marco Gerritsen, a "Mother of Srebrenica" Maunira Subasic, and lawyers Faruli Capina and Semir Guzin on their way to deliver a civil summons at the Dutch Supreme Court in the Hague, 04 Jun 2007 Survivors and relatives of victims of the 1995 Srebrenica massacre are taking legal action against the United Nations and the Dutch government for failing to protect Muslim civilians in the U.N. safe haven. Lawyers for the group "Mothers of Srebrenica" filed suit Monday in The Hague. The class action suit accuses the Dutch government of failing to authorize air cover to prevent the massacre - which is considered the worst genocide in Europe since the end of World War II. Serb forces slaughtered up to 8,000 Muslim men and boys after capturing the town. Dutch forces operating under a U.N. mandate were assigned to protect the enclave, which had been declared a U.N. safe zone to protect Muslims from Bosnian Serb attacks. When calls for protective airstrikes were denied, about 450 lightly-armed Dutch peacekeepers allowed Serb forces into the town and failed to prevent the Serbs from taking away the victims. Ten principal plaintiffs are each asking for $34,000 in damages. A 2002 report blamed politicians for sending Dutch U.N. troops on an impossible mission. The findings led to the resignation of the Dutch government. Last December, Srebrenica survivors expressed their outrage when the Dutch government gave medals to the peacekeepers. Earlier this year, the International Court of Justice dismissed a claim filed by Bosnia - Herzegovina against Serbia, which sought compensation for the genocide. Some information for this report was provided by AFP, AP and Reuters. Key Srebrenica Massacre Suspect Transferred To UN Tribunal Serbia Investigates 12 for War Crimes in Croatia Bush to Discuss Missile Defense in Czech Republic Al-Qaida Linked Groups Says it Killed Missing American Soldiers in Iraq Lebanese Army Clashes With Militants in 2nd Palestinian Refugee Camp Israeli Military Orders 3 Hamas Members Held for 6 Months Charles Taylor Boycotts His War Crimes Trial in The Hague US Defense Secretary Says Iranian Weapons Reach Taleban China Promises to Fight Climate Change, Rejects Emission Caps Dati Becomes First Muslim to Hold Key Position in France's Cabinet Summit of American Nations Opens to Address Energy Concerns Terms of Use & Privacy Notice Broadcasting Board of Governors
