http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/8-2&fd=R&url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/ap/world/4860352.html&cid=1116878342&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg 6 Day War, 40 years of lost Mideast hope | Chron.com - Houston Chronicle " width="11" height="11" border="0"> Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Legal & Public Notices Travel News & Features Legal & Public Notices June 4, 2007, 2:45PM 6 Day War, 40 years of lost Mideast hope By MARK LAVIE Associated Press Writer &copy; 2007 The Associated Press JERUSALEM &mdash; A grudging handshake on the White House lawn promised two peoples what they so desperately craved: for the Palestinians, a state of their own, for the Israelis, peace and quiet. Soon after, the two sides returned to violence. That squandered moment of hope in 1993 has been the trend for 40 years since Israel seized the West Bank from Jordan and the Gaza Strip from Egypt in the Six Day War. As Palestinians and Israelis mark the anniversary Tuesday of the start of that war, a majority of both now favor two states side by side &mdash; a goal that remains frustratingly out of reach. On Sept. 13, 1993, then-President Clinton nudged Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in the direction of Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin after the two signed the first-ever agreement between their two peoples &mdash; a framework for peace. Rabin needed a push from his foreign minister to extend his hand to Arafat. The reluctant handshake now seems like an omen that things would not go so smoothly. After five years of largely fruitless negotiations, the peace process gave way to violence. It has been the pattern since 1967: brief high points overwhelmed in a sea of bloody Palestinian attacks and Israeli military operations and restrictions. After Israel routed Egypt and Syria and pushed the Jordanian military out of east Jerusalem and the West Bank, Israelis and Palestinians were in contrasting states of shock. Israelis by the tens of thousands streamed to Jerusalem to see and touch the holiest site in Judaism, the Western Wall, off limits to them and under Jordanian control since 1949. Others traveled to biblical sites in the West Bank. The ecstasy was so great that many talked of the coming of the Messiah. At the same time, terrified Palestinians cowered in their houses, many expecting pain and death at the hands of the Israeli military, which had just vanquished the best of the Arab war machine in less than a week. At first, Israelis did not accept that there was such a thing as a Palestinian people. Then they believed that if they treated the Palestinians well enough, they would drop the political ambitions of exiled leaders like Arafat. In June 1987, the Israeli Civil Administration, an arm of the military, put out a full-color booklet trumpeting Israel's accomplishments during its two decades in control of the West Bank and Gaza, giving the Palestinian people roads, schools, hospitals and prosperity. But Palestinians chafed under the occupation, and just five months later the situation blew up. Gaza, then the West Bank, erupted in riots. Israeli forces tried to put them down, killing demonstrators throwing rocks and firebombs. At the center of the uprising were young Palestinians who grew up under Israeli occupation and demanded its end. The violence forced Israel into negotiations with Arafat's PLO, in secret at first and then publicly, leading to that handshake on the White House lawn. Arafat made a triumphant return to Gaza in 1994, and both sides felt peace was on the way. They were wrong. Agreements were negotiated but not fully implemented. Israel pulled out of West Bank cities and refugee camps, but kept a tight hold on Palestinian life. Palestinians smuggled large quantities of weapons into their areas, preparing for more clashes. When violence erupted again in September 2000, it seemed inevitable. The last seven years have seen more than 100 Palestinian suicide bombing attacks against Israelis and intense Israeli military incursions in the West Bank and Gaza. Even Israel's unilateral pullout from Gaza in 2005 didn't stem the chaos, with the impoverished coastal strip deteriorating into anarchic world of gang wars and attacks on Israel that invite retaliation. On Sunday, Israeli tanks and infantry pushed a short distance into Gaza, detaining several Palestinians in their fight against gunmen. Years of polls show both sides want a state living in peace next to the other state, but their leaders have proved unable to overcome the historic stumbling blocks, especially control over Jerusalem and a solution for Palestinian refugees from the 1948-49 war that followed Israel's creation. Israel's grim reality is typified by extreme security &mdash; guards checking bags for bombs at the entrances to buildings, ex-generals routinely elected to positions of leadership, the military maintaining a strong influence in the country. Palestinians suffer daily. Hundreds of Israeli roadblocks stop them from moving freely in the West Bank, Gaza is often cut off from the world, their economy is stifled and their lives are dominated by the ever-present Israeli soldier, bureaucrat or roadblock. Now Israel is building a barrier along the West Bank, jutting into the territory in several places, ostensibly to stop suicide bombers from entering Israel. It's a wall that marks a border in time &mdash; hopes of peaceful coexistence in the past, a reality of violence and hatred in the present. Australian remains in Vietnam head home 1,683 guitarists play 'Smoke on Water' Egypt: No to ancient pyramids on stamp France sets quotas for immigrant arrests Indonesian kangaroos to gain freedom Silva proposes forest preservation plan Landslide damages famed valley in Russia Bush says he sees an opening for peace Anger, unease 40 years after Mideast war Abbas says new regime to accept Israel Israeli leaders offer little regret but some hope for new start Sharon's predecessors share stage in Gaza drama Israel retaliates for killings with 2 attacks Abbas seeks to inherit Palestinian leadership Palestinian bomb suspect gunned down from long range Arafat buried after tumultuous West Bank scene Arafat's death leaves cloud of uncertainty Buy Photos & Page Prints 2005-Present Historic Page Prints 1901-2004 Copyright Notice & Privacy Policy
http://www.smh.com.au/news/world/football-fans-perish-in-helicopter-crash/2007/06/04/1180809374972.html&cid Football fans perish in helicopter crash - World - smh.com.au Welcome to The Sydney Morning Herald. Football fans perish in helicopter crash June 4, 2007 - 8:46AM A helicopter carrying Togolese soccer fans to Sierra Leone's main airport has crashed, killing 21 of the 22 people on board. The Paramount Airlines helicopter, operating between Freetown and Lungi international airport, caught fire as it was descending in preparation for landing at the airport, senior airport maintenance officer Alfred Yelinkeh said. "It was shocking to see the helicopter disintegrating,'' Yelinkeh said. Most of the dead were supporters of the Togo national soccer team, including the country's sports minister who had travelled to Freetown to cheer their team, which beat Sierra Leone 1-0 in an African Cup of Nations elimination match, a local radio station reported. Togolese sports officials had apparently chartered the helicopter to catch their flight back to Togo. Paramount Airlines is one of two commercial companies that run helicopter services between Freetown and Lungi airport, ferrying passengers in a seven-minute flight over the Sierra Leone river. Helicopters and a sea ferry are the only ways to get to the airport, located across a bay from the capital, Freetown, which is on the Atlantic Ocean. A witness said the helicopter apparently developed a problem in the air and both pilots jumped out, with one of them surviving. She said the helicopter burst into flames upon crashing, and was destroyed before airport firefighters could put out the flames. In 2001, a UN helicopter travelling from UN headquarters in Sierra Leone to the airport crashed into the bay, killing all seven aboard. The UN said at the time a mechanical problem appeared to have been the cause. British Prime Minister Tony Blair paid a one-day trip to Sierra Leone, a former British colony, last week as part of a farewell tour to Africa. send photos, videos & tip-offs to 0424 SMS SMH (+61 424 767 764), or us. on home delivery of the Herald - subscribe today Football fans perish in helicopter crash Place a classified ad Copyright &#169; 2007. The Sydney Morning Herald. Browse for a Date It's agreed: candidates court left Somali PM escapes new assassination attempt Man of letters kept historic collection in laundry Putin's missile threat to Europe Poverty-stricken loner behind JFK airport plot Israelis see dire echoes in boycott Bernstein book reveals why Hillary stood by Bill Tears as mother bids farewell to her nationality Triumph of mateship brings diggers home Men accused of flight rampage deported Aussie businessmen to be deported from UAE Hard sell for Oz music Crusty nominations for most-played Australian song around the world. Welcome to your future Ten experts predict what Australia will be like in 2027. Forewarned is fore-armed, so catch this illuminating doco about the history of jihad. All Men Are Liars: Gender inequality, the root of all evil. Sam and the City: If women ran the world, would sh*t get done? On the Australia set Sneak preview behind the scenes of the movie with Baz Luhrmann. Nudes leave tail ends out Hundreds pose naked in an Amsterdam car park. TODAY'S TOP 10 ARTICLES Lonely Planet author missing High-speed broadband to woo voters Poverty-stricken loner behind JFK airport plot Smile, you're on Google's candid camera Muffin top is a word lover's barbecue stopper Five weeks a year on a train Knoxville sued over mousetrap stunt Photographer snaps 2000 nudes in Amsterdam Paris Hilton starts jail term Hewitt bids 'au revoir' to French Open More most viewed articles News Store Alert will keep you informed. Get free news emails from smh.com.au.
