urrent Constitution, the President can be elected to a maximum of two consecutive four-year terms. The prospect of Putin remaining in power for a third presidential term after 2008, when his current term expires, has been widely debated in Russia, although he himself has repeatedly said he will not run for the top post again. "I believe that the limitation by the number of terms is justified," he said, however adding, that four years is too short a term for the President of a country like Russia. "In modern Russia, five, six or seven years is quite acceptable," he said. Putin said he had been Prime Minister and acting President before elections and he knew "what was going on and what was involved in the decision-making process". "But if, for example, a Governor is elected (President), it will take him at least two years to understand national and international problems, but by then a new election campaign will have to be launched," Putin said. *Your friend's e-mail address: Liberia`s Taylor boycotts war crimes trial US troops surge in Iraq short of goal: Report Harry may be barred from Afghanistan too Bush to revive old friendships, forge new ones at G8 summit Yahoo! India Job Search! Get $5 USD in Free Calls! Live Cricket Ball by Ball SMS CRIC TO 7575 Express Gifts -Delivery in 24 Hrs. Post your free ad now! Persquareyard.com. Complete real estate portal. Book Classified Ads in Leading Newspapers Get instant response for your ads. Astro Predictions for You 100000+ Live ads. Post your ad. Travelling to India - Best Value Fantastic Travel deals! Plan UR trip Submit your details & save on airfares Zero Cost Money Transfers. Hurry! Get your super-saver NRI Account Yahoo! India Job Search . NRIs, One-stop shop for all your needs. Send Gifts to India Copyright &copy; Zee News Limited. All rights reserved.
http://english.sabah.com.tr/DCFD77D951644D85A24D42DDB2A7F127.html&cid Array ( [0] => DCFD77D951644D85A24D42DDB2A7F127 [1] => 804667EACF7D4AAD8D7597E477449DF3 ) SABAH Newspaper English Edition - World - Pole wakes from 19-year coma in democratic country Monday, 04 June 2007 Pole wakes from 19-year coma in democratic country A 65-year-old railwayman, who fell into a coma following an accident in communist Poland, regained consciousness 19 years later to find democracy and a market economy, Polish media reported on Saturday. Pole wakes from 19-year coma in democratic country A 65-year-old railwayman, who fell into a coma following an accident in communist Poland, regained consciousness 19 years later to find democracy and a market economy, Polish media reported on Saturday. Wheelchair-bound Jan Grzebski, whom doctors had given only two or three years to live following his 1988 accident, credited his caring wife Gertruda with his revival. "It was Gertruda that saved me, and I'll never forget it" Grzebski told news channel TVN24. "For 19 years Mrs Grzebska did the job of an experienced intensive care team, changing her comatose husband's position every hour to prevent bed-sore infections," Super Express reported Dr Boguslaw Poniatowski as saying. "When I went into a coma there was only tea and vinegar in the shops, meat was rationed and huge petrol queues were everywhere," Grzebski told TVN24, describing his recollections of the communist system's economic collapse. "Now I see people on the streets with cell phones and there are so many goods in the shops it makes my head spin." Grzebski awoke to find his four children had all married and produced 11 grandchildren during his years in the hospital. He said he vaguely recalled the family gatherings he was taken to while in a coma and his wife and children trying to communicate with him. E-mail this to a friend Dead man rides on tram all night Paris Hilton starts serving jail term Putin warns he will point missiles at Europ