ext of the kin of all those killed in the violence. During the talks, state health minister Digamber Singh assisted Raje, while Bainsla was accompanied by an 11-member delegation. Bainsla said the agitation of the Gujjar community would continue peacefully if their demand for shifting the Gujjars from OBC to Scheduled Tribe category was not recommended by the state government to the Centre. Your comment[s] on this article Be the first to comment on this story. CPI(M) asks SFI to formulate new ideas BJP likely to reschedule Jaipur meet JJ Irani Committee On Company Law Run-Up To Foreign Trade Policy 2005-06 Run Up To Budget 2007-08 Rbi Annual Policy 2007-08 Run-Up To Budget 2005-06 Ear To The Ground The Indian Express Group &copy; 2007: Indian Express Newspapers (Mumbai) Ltd. All rights reserved throughout the world.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/4-0&fd=R&url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2007/06/04/news/leb.php&cid=1116516999&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg Lebanon Army keeps up siege of Palestinian camps - International Herald Tribune Subscribe to the newspaper Find out more >> Africa &#038; Middle East Remove all read clippings Lebanon Army keeps up siege of Palestinian camps By Hassan M. Fattah Published: June 4, 2007 Two soldiers and two militants were killed in fighting in the Palestinian refugee camp Ein al Hilweh in southern Lebanon early Monday, sparking fears that the army&#039;s 16-day siege of the Nahr al Bared camp in the north could spread further. In a series of skirmishes that began Sunday afternoon, militants with the Islamist group Jund al Sham opened fire on Lebanese Army soldiers, sparking a violent firefight that left numerous houses inside the camp ablaze and ultimately resulted in the death of the four men, military officials said. Meanwhile, 100 kilometers, or 60 miles, north at the Nahr al Bared camp, Lebanese troops continued an offensive against Fatah al Islam, putting the camp under a hail of machine gun fire and shelling from Sunday into early Monday. At least 114 people have been killed in the siege of the camp, which began when security men raided an apartment in Tripoli seeking bank robbers and touching off the fight with Fatah al Islam. The violence eased in both camps Monday afternoon as Palestinian and religious leaders sought to calm tempers in Ein al Hilweh and to negotiate an end to the siege at Nahr al Bared. Today in Africa &#038; Middle East Dreams of college destroyed in Iraq Militant video shows missing soldiers&#x27; IDs Lebanon Army keeps up siege of Palestinian camps Palestinian factions met with the army command in Sidon on Monday morning, as heavily armed Jund al Sham fighters agreed to cede their positions to militiamen from other Islamist groups at Ein al Hilweh, where more than 47,000 refugees live. Despite sporadic gunfire in Nahr al Bared, aid agencies worked to get water and food into the camp. Red Cross officials said a few civilians had managed to escape the camp. The United Nations&#039; aid agency warned that conditions inside were worsening significantly and made an appeal for new funds to help those who had fled. Thousands of refugees from the camp have escaped in the past two weeks, but aid groups estimated that about 6,000 residents are trapped inside. Reporters have been pushed back out of sight of the fighting, making it difficult to confirm reports from both sides. The Lebanese Army continued to reinforce its positions at Nahr al Bared and brought in more armor, men and supplies, possibly in preparation for another push against Fatah al Islam. A tenuous calm held through much of Monday. But an empty bus in an industrial area north of Beirut was hit by a bomb Monday night and 10 people nearby were wounded. Africa &#038; Middle East Meanwhile: I am, therefore I need to dance The four circles of a changing world Speakers bureaus give book authors a new income stream Beijing climate-change strategy has no emission caps 3 mild earthquakes rattle New Hampshire Drug may be first effective medication for liver cancer Hear the first victims of climate change Russia says it will target European sites if U.S. missile shield proceeds Inmates say Paris Hilton is in for a stay in &#39;hell&#39; Commanders say push in Baghdad is short of goal U.S. government fights to keep meatpackers from testing all slaughtered cattle for mad cow Islam taking root in Turkey&#39;s bureaucracy No more the &#39;hopeless continent&#39; Corruption in China: The anger boils over Chinese drug commissioner is sentenced to death Understanding and coping with tremors An escapee tells of life and death in North Korea&#39;s labor camps Malaysia rejects Muslim convert&#39;s bid to be recognized as Christian A rare glimpse of 19th-century Iran With allies in enemy ranks, GIs in Iraq are no longer true believers Ge