 or seven years would be right for Russia,â€ he said. â€œFour years, of course, is a fairly short term.â€ â€œFor todayâ€™s Russia, five, six, or seven years is quite acceptable, however, the number of terms should be limited.â€ Mr Putin added that while he had been prime minister for several months before becoming president, if someone such as a regional governor were elected president, it might take him two years to settle into the job. By then, in a four-year term, it was already time to start the next election campaign. Politicians from both houses of Russiaâ€™s parliament quickly rallied behind Mr Putinâ€™s suggestion â€“ which some analysts have suggested could provide a pretext for his early return as president. Political analysts have suggested Mr Putin could step down next March, complying with the letter of the constitution and thereby enabling him to vaunt his democratic credentials. If the constitution were then changed to lengthen the presidential term, that could provide a pretext for new elections in which Mr Putin would be constitutionally entitled to participate, analysts have said. Mr Mironov called two months ago for Mr Putin to remain as president for a third term, the most senior politician to do so. Last week, he declared the matter â€œclosedâ€ since Mr Putin had made clear he would go next year â€“ but Mr Mironov continued to voice support for lengthening the presidential term. He noted with satisfaction on Monday that Mr Putin had supported his call. Lyubov Sliska, first deputy speaker of Russiaâ€™s lower house and a leading member of the pro-Putin United Russia party, said Mr Putinâ€™s proposal was â€œrightâ€. â€œFor such a huge country as Russia, it would be realistic [for a president] to serve three terms of five years, or two terms of seven years,â€ she said. Vladimir Pligin, head of the lower houseâ€™s constitutional legislation committee, also backed the idea, but said it could only apply to the next president. â€œIn such a complex country and with such complex tasks the optimal term length for a president could be seven years,â€ he said. Alexander Ter-Avanesov, deputy head of the regional policy committee of Russiaâ€™s upper house, told Interfax news agency Mr Putinâ€™s words were in effect the beginning of the process of changing the constitution to extend the presidential term. The Financial Times Limited 2007 - create a keyword alert on the subject of this topic - download our application to receive instant alerts on this topic - start your day with daily email briefing on this topic - Track this news topic using our feeds Future of Europe 2007 "Middle East" sub navigation "By sector" sub navigation "By region" sub navigation "Markets headlines" sub navigation "Market data" sub navigation Australia & New Zealand "Managed funds" sub navigation "Comment & Analysis" sub navigation Comment & Analysis main "Debates and polls" sub navigation Debates and polls main "Video & Audio" sub navigation Video & Audio main View from the Top "Business Life" sub navigation "Business education" sub navigation Features of the week "Your Money" sub navigation "Advice & comment" sub navigation Advice & comment main "Compare & apply" sub navigation Compare & apply main "Arts & Weekend" sub navigation Arts & Weekend main How to spend it "Weekend columnists" sub navigation "In depth" sub navigation "Special Reports" sub navigation Future of Europe 2007 "Jobs & classified" sub navigation Jobs & classified main "Services & tools" sub navigation Services & tools main "News tracking" sub navigation News feeds and alerts Get FT RSS feeds Add FT news feeds to your blog or website Get FT news on your mobile Minimum delay 15 minutes All times are London time Advertise with the FT The Financial Times Ltd 2007. "FT" and "Financial Times" are trademarks of The Financial Times Ltd. considers the likelihood of a breakthough on trade at this weekâ€™s meeting View from the top : Andrew Liveris, CEO of Dow Chemical, talks about the sa