r, thanks to Ma Lik, the whole controversy has been stirred up again. Until China reverses its verdict on the massacre, a lot of people will always demonstrate. Itâ€™s difficult for us to forget that our government came out and killed peaceful demonstrators. China will have to face up to what it did first. In Taiwan, the anniversary serves to remind people what kind of government mainland China has. How do you interpret what Ma Lik said? I think he was testing the water. Someone in Beijing must have asked him to see how people would react so that they could begin rewriting textbooks and set about trying to erase peopleâ€™s memories of June 4th. Ma Lik is a very cautious person, and he wouldnâ€™t have done such a thing on his own. If it was a test, what did it show? That we havenâ€™t changed. Actually, I think Ma Lik succeeded in attracting a lot more people to tonightâ€™s candlelight vigil. Congressman indicted on 16 counts Al-Qaida group: Abducted GIs slain Putin offers warning on U.S. plan Charges nixed for Gitmo detainee Democrats debate in N.H. N. Korea: Decoding Conflicting Info on Kim Capital Sources: The Art of Interrogation Hosenball: The Trinidad Terror Connection Remembering the Dead of Tiananmen Musings on the Democratic Debate N. Korea: Decoding Conflicting Info on Kim Capital Sources: The Art of Interrogation Hosenball: The Trinidad Terror Connection Remembering the Dead of Tiananmen Musings on the Democratic Debate Subscribe to Newsweek &#151; Lowest Rate Available Add Newsweek RSS Feeds RIGHTS AND REPRINT SALES ONLINE AND DISTANCE LEARNING DIRECTORY
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/6-2&fd=R&url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_pictures/6719415.stm&cid=1116948212&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg BBC NEWS | In Pictures | In pictures: Tiananmen remembered The News in 2 minutes Your news when you want it Also in the news Monday, 4 June 2007, 14:31 GMT 15:31 UK E-mail this to a friend In pictures: Tiananmen remembered A black wreath flies to mark the 18th anniversary of a bloody crackdown on peaceful protests in Tiananmen Square, Beijing. Tens of thousands attended a candlelight vigil in Hong Kong - an annual event that is always well attended. Hong Kong is the only part of China's territory that is allowed to commemorate the events of Tiananmen. In Tiananmen Square itself, the day began as always with a flag-raising ceremony, watched by a small number of onlookers. Security was reportedly tight around the square, which in 1989 was the scene of weeks of pro-democracy demonstrations. On 4 June 1989, the Chinese government sent in its troops - leading to the deaths of many students and civilians. Beijing has always refused to apologise, saying the action was necessary to stop what it called a counter-revolutionary uprising. E-mail this to a friend TOP IN PICTURES STORIES Day in pictures: 4 June MOST POPULAR STORIES NOW Launch date for iPhone revealed Cameroon girls battle 'breast ironing' Hirst unveils £50m diamond skull S Africa police clash with nurses Greek man shot in double-park row Most popular now, in detail Nato condemns Putin missile vow Moroccan family barred from toilet Greek man shot in double-park row Guantanamo Canadian case dropped Your alternative Olympic logos Most popular now, in detail Mixed views in Sierra Leone and Liberia to the Charles Taylor trial Preview the Royal Academy's Summer Exhibition 2007 Living in a toilet The Moroccan family blocked from going home - to a public loo Back to top ^^ Privacy and cookies policy
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/17-2&fd=R&url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6719741.stm&cid=1116579515&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg BBC NEWS | Europe | Bosnia suspect attacks UN arrest The News in 2 minutes Your news when you want it Also in the news Monday, 4 June 2007, 18:21 GMT 19:21 UK E-mail this to a friend Bosnia suspect attacks UN arrest Gen Tolimir is a suspect in the 1995 Srebrenica massacre A former Bosnian Serb intelligence chief arrested last week has accused UN prosecutors in The Hague of breaking their own rules in arresting him. In his first court hearing, Gen Zdravko Tolimir said he had been sent against his will to the Bosnian Serb republic, even though he is a citizen of Serbia. UN war crimes tribunal chief prosecutor Carla Del Ponte is visiting Serbia to assess its co-operation with the court. The EU has pledged to resume talks soon on closer ties with Serbia. Tolimir, 58, did not enter a plea to charges of genocide, extermination, persecution and inhumane acts. He told the court he had suffered three strokes and lost around 30kg, and said that he was unlawfully extradited to the Bosnian Serb republic (Republika Srpska). Carla Del Ponte is dealing with a new Serbian government "I was arrested in the territory of Serbia, whose citizen I am, and I was transferred to the territory of [Republika Srpska] ... without the presence of a lawyer," Gen Tolimir said. He was reportedly arrested following a tip-off from Serbian police after spending years on the run. He was a top aide to Gen Ratko Mladic, the most-wanted former Bosnian Serb commander, who is still on the run. His arrest reduced to five the number of indicted war crimes suspects still at large. He is accused of involvement in the Srebrenica massacre of up to 8,000 Muslim men and boys in eastern Bosnia in 1995. Ms Del Ponte's visit was requested by the new Serbian government, which wants her to assess its co-operation with the court. She has repeatedly urged Belgrade to capture Gen Mladic. The European Union suspended talks with Serbia a year ago because of Belgrade's failure to co-operate with the court. The resumption date will depend on Ms Del Ponte's assessment. EU Enlargement Commissioner Olli Rehn has said he expects the talks to resume later this month. E-mail this to a friend Tolimir arrest fuels speculation that Mladic may be next Genocide ruling frustrates Bosnia Hunt for Karadzic and Mladic Will Mladic face justice? Shattered lives in Srebrenica Karadzic and Mladic: The charges Hague tribunal at a glance What is a war crime? The BBC is not responsible for the content of external internet sites Nato condemns Putin missile threat Seven Turks killed in rebel raid Hague trial for Liberian ex-leader MOST POPULAR STORIES NOW Launch date for iPhone revealed Cameroon girls battle 'breast ironing' Hirst unveils £50m diamond skull S Africa police clash with nurses Greek man shot in double-park row Most popular now, in detail Nato condemns Putin missile vow Moroccan family barred from toilet Greek man shot in double-park row Guantanamo Canadian case dropped Your alternative Olympic logos Most popular now, in detail Mixed views in Sierra Leone and Liberia to the Charles Taylor trial Preview the Royal Academy's Summer Exhibition 2007 Living in a toilet The Moroccan family blocked from going home - to a public loo Back to top ^^ Privacy and cookies policy
