http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-1&fd=R&url=http://www.dnaindia.com/report.asp%3FNewsID%3D1101249&cid=1116969380&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg DNA - Opinion - Bush turns green - Daily News & Analysis Open in new window Monday, June 04, 2007 22:05 IST To reprint this article, contact US President George W Bush’s latest plan to combat climate change through an American initiative has evoked justifiable scorn and scepticism, especially in Europe. Bush is trying to redeem his Presidency and the tattered American reputation in the wake of the disastrous war in Iraq, but it is not clear whether he is serious and sincere. After steadfastly refusing to heed the warning signals over the deepening crisis of climate change for the greater part of his two Presidential terms, he now wants to emerge as the champion of the green cause. The Bush rethinking on the issue is quite similar to that on the war in Iraq. In 2003, President Bush was contemptuous of the United Nations, and he did not think that UN mandate was necessary to go ahead with the war. But after two years, the US went back to the UN and sought a mandate to handle the unsettled situation in Iraq. Similarly, the Americans now realise that they have been marginalised on the most important issue facing the international community. But instead of being penitent, they want to pretend that they will lead the world in grappling with the problem of greenhouse gas emissions and the consequential climate change. What is more, the US wants to take along other countries, including India and China, in this latest initiative. In 1997, the US had refused to sign the Kyoto Protocol which set the goal of reducing greenhouse gas emissions to 50 per cent of 1990 levels by 2020. Its simplistic argument was that the US cannot afford to place its economic growth in jeopardy, though the European Union (EU), which is the strongest advocate of Kyoto Protocol, had argued that economic growth and environment-friendly measures are not incompatible. Of course, the US has not changed its position on Kyoto Protocol goals. Instead, Bush is offering to spend money on research and development to create cleaner technologies and to set long-term goals to meet the challenge of climate change. He continues to skirt the Kyoto Protocol, but is also trying at the same time to keep the US in the picture with regard to future initiatives on environmental issues. The Kyoto Protocol ends in 2012, and it is time for a fresh round of talks, a new agenda and new goals. Bush wants to take the US back into the international community’s green initiatives, though in the American way. It is true that without the Americans on board, no plan to combat climate change will be effective because American lifestyles generate the most pollution. Therefore, it will be necessary for EU and others to humour the US so that it can join the collective effort. More articles in Opinion &#187; Kalam is a threat to the political class Be the first to rate this article! (This name will appear below your comment.) (Will not be published.) (Please note: Comment moderation is enabled and may delay your comment. There is no need to resubmit your comment.) Get daily news in your inbox and read it at your convenience. Putin warns retribution for US missile system The big coach hunt Whatmore out, Ford is prime contender for India job Rajasthan burns... Delhi, NCR feel the heat Reliance Fresh set for a roll-out in Mumbai Shilpa Shetty to be honoured at IIFA for global impact BJP hopes hinge on an IITian engineer in Goa Cricket board to name new coach today My film not adapted: Siddharth Anand CMDA erred in sending notice to AIADMK: MK Al Gore against any attempt to impeach Bush Chennai's land prices costlier than London Woman commits suicide as husband refuses to have sex Google to make Web work offline Bollywood in the Big Apple Microsoft rethinks computer with coffee-table design The Universe is Riyo's! Mel Gibson buys $25.8m ranch in Costa Rica 