http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/12-3&fd=R&url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,21842642-663,00.html&cid=1116909385&ei=iIBkRvuXH5qoqgPgxPSZBg Pole's big sleep | Herald Sun Welcome to Herald Sun. Send a Letter to the Editor Corporate Photo Sales, Copyright Herald Sun Cartoons & Caricatures Memorabilia & Limited Editions Back Issues & Home Delivery Herald Sun - Sell your car for FREE Place a classified newspaper ad June 04, 2007 12:00am WHEN Pole Jan Grzebski, 46, was hit by a train, he plunged into a coma -- and was blasted two decades into the future. The father of four's last memories, from 1988, were of toiling as a railway worker under the communist regime of General Wojciech Jaruzelski. Now, after 19 years, Mr Grzebski has woken to an unimaginably changed country -- and he has found himself a 65-year-old grandfather of 11. "When I went into a coma there was only tea and vinegar in the shops, meat was rationed, and huge petrol lines were everywhere," Mr Grzebski told Polish TV. "Now there are so many goods in the shops, it makes my head spin." Elections the year after his accident led to eastern Europe's first post-communist government. Poland joined NATO in 1999 and the EU in 2004. Mr Grzebski says he is alive thanks to his wife's constant care, after doctors gave him just two or three years to live. "It was Gertruda that saved me and I'll never forget it," he said. Mr Grzebski finds much to marvel at. "All these people who walk around with their mobile phones and never stop moaning," he said. "I've got nothing to complain about." Liberian regime brought to trial Clinton rebuffs stinging Iraq attack China warms to dirty fight Fine art of doing nothing JFK airport plot suspects appear in court Tiananmen quiet on anniversary of crackdown Police accused of Timor rally shootings Putin threatens to point missiles at Europe Dragon mauls boy to death Five years of life spent worrying Harry 'just one of the boys' at military camp Hustler offers $